<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Germany-PlaneCrash 11thLd-Writethru   08-28 1029</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Plane Crash, 11th Ld - Writethru,a0801,1060</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Jets Crash At Air Show; 46 Killed, 500 Injured</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 10th pvs, `A third...' to UPDATE with
air show next month canceled, protests before Sunday's show; picks
up 11th pvs: Mrs. Banks...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMSTEIN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Italian fighter jets crashed
during an air show at a U.S. military base Sunday, and one swooped
into the crowd and burst into a huge fireball. At least 46 people
died and hundreds were hurt, officials said.
   Several children and the three aircraft pilots, members of a
famed aerial stunt team, were among the dead at the Ramstein Air
Base, about 60 miles southwest of Frankfurt, authorities reported.
   A giant ball of flame engulfed fleeing spectators when one
aircraft hit the ground, sending many screaming with their clothes
on fire. Television footage showed cars and trucks in flames.
   Some people stood in shock as a thick cloud of smoke enveloped
them, and others ran toward the scene to administer aid.
   News reports said 500 people were injured, nearly half of them
hospitalized.
   ``It was horrible, horrible, a huge shock,'' said Krista Banks,
a West German who works as a waitress at the base. ``It's going to
take a long time to forget this.''
   West German officials estimated the size of the crowd at the air
show at 200,000, and said most were Americans and Germans.
   U.S. and West German officials said the cause of the triple
crash was unknown and the exact sequence of events was unclear.
   But it appeared two of the Aermacchi MB 339As collided head-on
during a complex manuever by the 10-aircraft stunt team, then
crashed away from the crowd.
   A third jet veered uncontrollably out of formation, flames
spewing from its fuselage, and headed toward the crowd, then
exploded into a huge fireball an estimated 100 feet high.
   The Ramstein air show has drawn protests for several years
because of possible dangers to civilians. Demonstrators already
were protesting outside the base's gates as Sunday's air show began.
   West German Defense Minister Rupert Scholz immediately canceled
an air show by West German warplanes planned for September, and
asked the country's NATO partners to consider ``following these
same measures for the time being.''
   Mrs. Banks, wife of an American who is a U.S. Army employee,
said she was in the control tower when the accident occurred.
   ``There was a big flash of flame and smoke, and people were
running away. Everyone at the tower was in shock,'' said Mrs. Banks.
   ``We saw the fireball racing toward us, so we first threw
ourselves down on the ground,'' said Detlef Hosser, cameraman with
the ARD television network.
   Television footage had one man frantically shrieking ``Tanya,
Tanya'' and thousands of others screaming and looking for friends
and family members.
   Hans-Juergen Vollmer, spokesman for the Kaiserslautern
administrative area that includes Ramstein, said he believed the
crash started from a pilot's mistake.
   ``It looks as though it (the accident) was caused by pilot
error,'' he told The Associated Press.
   The three jets were part of a 10-plane Italian Air Force
demonstration team, ``Frecce Tricolori,'' that was flying 65 yards
above the ground.
   The ``Frecce Tricolori,'' which means Tri-Color Arrows and
refers to the three-colored Italian flag, was founded in 1930 as a
school of aerobatics. Since 1956, it has been a separate unit of
the Italian air force based at Rivolto.
   Ramstein Air Base spokesman Doug Moore said ``those dead on the
ground are a mix of civilian and military.''
   AFN, the U.S. military radio network, said late Sunday the
latest confirmed death toll was 46.
   About 500 people were injured, the West German television
network ZDF said late Sunday. The Norddeutschfunk radio station
said about 230 people were still hospitalized, many with serious
burns.
   ``A large number has serious burns,'' said police spokesman
Willi Hollaender in nearby Kaiserslautern.
   ``There are many children among the dead and injured,'' said
Kris Kumpf, a German medical assistant who helped treat the
injured. ``The worst part of it is, we're still trying to find some
of the parents,'' she said, trying to hold back tears.
   She said most of the injured had badly burned backs from when
they turned and tried to run away from the flaming jet.
   Moore said investigators were still piecing together the
sequence of events. He said it was not certain whether all three
planes collided at once or whether two first hit each other and the
third later become involved.
   The Italian news agency ANSA said the planes apparently were
participating in a difficult heart-shaped maneuver when the
collision occurred.
   It said the maneuver involves nine aircraft flying toward the
runway and then climbing. At a certain point in the ascent, they
break into two groups that form giant loops and then pass each
other in opposite directions. A solo flier passes through the
formation to add drama.
   It said the disaster at Ramstein apparently happened when the
two groups of planes were passing each other at about 250 mph.
   The agency did not cite its sources, but it said the conclusion
was based on the first examination of films of the crash arriving
in Italy from West Germany.
   Willi Hollaender, a police spokesman in Kaiserslautern, told the
AP that the planes involved were Aermacchi MB 339As, a two-seat
attack aircraft that the Italian air force also uses for pilot
training.
   Officials identified the three pilots killed Sunday as Lt. Col.
Mario Naldini, 41, Lt. Col. Ivo Nutarelli, 38, and Capt. Giorgio
Alessio, 31.
   The accident is believed to be the worst air show disaster
involving spectators in history. In September 1982, 46 people
aboard a U.S. Army helicopter carrying skydivers crashed during an
air show in Mannheim, West Germany.
   Several groups, including the environmentalist Greens party of
West Germany, oppose military air shows because of the potential
for such accidents.
   The crash sparked new calls for a ban on air shows.
   ``The events at Ramstein confirm in a really horrible way how
dangerous such spectacles are even for civilian observers,'' said
Walter Kolbow, a federal lawmaker for the opposition Social
Democratic Party.
</TEXT>
