<1ST_LINE>u a AM-GangViolence 1stLd-Writethru a0748 08-28 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gang Violence, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0748,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nine Killed Over Weekend; Police Increase Harbor Area Gang Patrol</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after 2nd to UPDATE with quote from news
conference.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LISA WOLFSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Street gang violence left at least nine dead
in Los Angeles and Riverside counties over the weekend, and Los
Angeles police hastily formed a task force to patrol a particularly
troubled area.
   Four people died in three separate shootings in the Harbor area,
one of several communities where there have been more gang deaths
this year than last year, Cmdr. William Booth of the Los Angeles
Police Department said Sunday. The Harbor district is about 25
miles south of downtown.
   ``We're going to increase patrol and go into homes of known gang
members to talk to parents,'' Booth said, adding that a meeting of
parents would be scheduled this week.
   In the latest attacks, one woman was killed and another wounded
early Sunday in the parking lot of a Harbor City housing project,
said Los Angeles police Sgt. James Allen. The dead woman's name was
withheld pending notification of relatives, Allen said.
   Several hours earlier and several blocks away, a 30-year-old man
was killed by gunman who sped away in a pickup truck, Allen said.
   A couple of miles to the east, two pedestrians _ a 16-year-old
youth and a 21-year-old man _ were killed and four others,
including an apparent innocent bystander, were wounded in a
gang-related shooting late Saturday night.
   In Southeast Los Angeles, ``a carload of gang members'' fired
about 20 shots from a semiautomatic pistol at a rival gang member,
killing an unidentified youth Saturday night, said Lt. Doug Young.
A 40-year-old man was also wounded.
   Two 26-year-old men were fatally shot early Saturday while
sitting on the balcony at a condominium complex in north Riverside,
55 miles east of Los Angeles, said police Sgt. Mike Wilson. Gang
slogans were shouted before the shooting, Wilson said.
   A 19-year-old youth was fatally shot early Saturday while
driving to visit his mother in Compton, police said. The shooting
occurred in a known gang hangout but authorities said they knew of
no motive for the crime.
   Inglewood police believed two shootings Friday night that
claimed the life of a 17-year-old and wounded two others were
committed by the same assailants, said Sgt. Ron Jackson.
</TEXT>
