<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BellyLanding 1stLd-Writethru a0640 08-28 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Belly Landing, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0640,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TWA Jet Makes Emergency Belly Landing At O'Hare Airport</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 2-3 to UPDATE with injuries being minor. Picks up
4th graf pvs, `TWA Flight ...' Subs 8th graf with 3 grafs to ADD
quotes about pilot joking to ease tension. Edits to conform and
tighten. No pick up.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A TWA jet carrying 68 people made a belly landing
Saturday at O'Hare International Airport after its landing gear
failed, and at least seven people were injured while evacuating on
chutes, authorities said.
   Nobody was seriously hurt, said officials at the four nearby
hospitals where the injured were taken.
   Five of them _ including a 102-year-old Chicago woman _ were
treated and released, while two were still getting care late
Saturday, one for a twisted ankle and the other for knee pains,
officials said.
   TWA Flight 524, en route from St. Louis to Chicago, was
approaching Midway Airport shortly before 4 p.m. when the pilot
noticed landing gear problems, said Donald Morrison, a TWA
spokesman in St. Louis.
   ``The captain was unable to lower the main landing gear,''
Morrison said. ``After following normal cockpit procedures trying
to lower it manually, he proceeded to O'Hare field,'' which has
longer runways and more emergency facilities than Midway.
   Fire engines, ambulances and other emergency vehicles converged
on the runway, which was sprayed with foam to ease the landing at
4:43 p.m., in foggy, rainy conditions.
   ``It came in beautifully, it didn't skid very far at all,'' said
Patrolman Jeff Nagle, who witnessed the landing. ``It was a perfect
landing on its belly, there was no gas leak or nothing.''
   Passenger Cassandra Walker, 22, of Hazelcrest, Ill., said that
when the crew announced the landing gear was not working, some
people aboard started crying. She said the mood on board was ``very
hysterical'' after the landing with tears of relief and happiness.
   She said at one point the pilot of the Boeing 727 attempted to
relieve tension by joking about a successful ``plane landing in
Honolulu with no top, so he could do it with no bottom.''
   The TWA pilot was referring to an April incident in which an
Aloha Airlines pilot landed a plane safely after an 18-foot section
of fuselage tore away, killing one person, during a flight from
Hilo, Hawaii, to Honolulu.
   The plane Saturday was carrying 62 passengers and six
crewmembers, Morrison said.
   The cause of the landing gear problem had not been determined,
and federal aviation officials will be investigating, Morrison said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
