<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-88 1117EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RollerCoaster     08-28 0660</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Roller Coaster,0678</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coaster So Terrifying Its Designer Isn't Allowed To Ride</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AGAWAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who designed the roller coaster
that many consider the nation's most terrifying had to get
permission to work on it and has never ridden his creation. His
doctor won't let him.
   ``About the time I got started on it, I had to have open heart
surgery,'' said William L. Cobb, 70, creator of the Cyclone at
Riverside Park in Agawam. ``My doctor said it would be all right to
work on it if I didn't get too excited about anything.''
   Rated best in the nation by American Coaster Enthusiasts when it
opened five years ago, the Cyclone is still the favorite of many
coaster buffs, although it is neither the largest nor the fastest.
   What it lacks in height and speed, it makes up for in
bone-jarring turns, says Paul L. Ruben, editor of RollerCoaster!,
the official magazine of ACE, a non-profit group of 1,700 coaster
fans. He calls it the most fearsome in memory.
   ``What you're facing here is a major league throwing machine,''
said Ruben, 51, an optical engineer from Penfield, N.Y. ``With this
coaster, you win if you don't get thrown out of your seat.''
   The Cyclone's cars swoop down a 112-foot drop at a 54-degree
angle into a turn at 60 mph. The ride then takes what Ruben calls
``fiendish'' boomerang twists along 3,200 feet of track, speeding
down two more extremely steep hills and throwing riders up, down
and against the sides of their seats at least nine times.
   ``It's weird to see the ground first and then the sky,'' said
Teddy Witt, 11, of Tolland, Conn., as he waited in line for his
second ride of the day.
   Although Ruben officially rates the Cyclone No. 2 behind the
Beast at Kings Island, Ohio _ the highest, longest and fastest
coaster in the country _ he says the coaster at Agawam, outside
Springfield, has no peer in terror.
   ``Every time I was airborne the thing would change direction and
try to pull the seat out from under me,'' he said.
   During a test run with sandbags a few hours before a 1983 news
conference, it bucked a few sandbags off.
   But the coaster has been the site of only one fall, by a rider
who suffered a fractured hip in 1983; witnesses said he unfastened
his safety restraints and stood up. A few months later, one of the
trains failed to stop and ran into the back of another, injuring
seven people.
   Park officials say there have been no injuries since, however.
   ``Ride safety is almost a religion among park operators,'' Ruben
said.
   Maintenance crews walk the coaster's rails every morning to
clear and check them and test-run the cars every day with sandbags.
Its operators say they argue several times daily with riders who
want to take along children too short to be held back by the safety
bar; there is a strictly enforced rider height minimum of 54 inches.
   ``People, kids too, they threaten us and they try to bribe us,''
said operator Don Shunney, 19.
   Cobb said the Cyclone was among the hardest coasters he has
designed in the last 20 years because of its tight space, a tight
construction deadline and the park's orders to create a ride that
would scare the daylights out of riders.
   ``They wanted people to think while they were riding it: `My
gosh, I'll never get off this thing alive,''' he said.
   Since the Cyclone, Cobb also designed Le Monstre in Montreal,
with two tracks that race against each other and with a 100-foot
twisting drop toward the St. Lawrence River.
   Cobb isn't all that upset that doctors won't let him ride his
creations.
   ``I never was a good rider,'' he admits. ``I was too critical.
If it didn't do exactly what I thought it should do, I would be
disappointed.''
</TEXT>
