<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Abortion-Couple     08-28 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion-Couple,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Couple Reunites After Husband's Lawsuit Over Wife's Abortion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DULUTH, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly two months after a judge refused to
stop a 27-year-old mother of three from having an abortion which
her husband vehemently opposed, Christine and Timothy Anderson are
back together.
   Although they haven't budged from their positions _ she supports
abortion rights and he's anti-abortion _ they say their 3-year-old
marriage now is better than ever.
   ``I respect his beliefs and he respects mine,'' Mrs. Anderson
said.
   When she learned she was pregnant a fourth time, she said, their
marriage was troubled and they had a mountain of debts.
   ``I kept looking at my kids,'' she said. ``I felt I had to have
an abortion so I could better provide for them.''
   In addition, they had agreed not to have more children. The
birth of their third child last year was difficult so Anderson
underwent a vasectomy, but it failed and she became pregnant three
months later.
   Anderson sued and obtained a temporary court order barring his
wife from having an abortion.
   Anderson's attorney, Rodney Brodin, argued that a man's right to
have a family should be balanced with a woman's right to have an
abortion.
   But on the morning of July 8, Mrs. Anderson waited at the
Women's Health Center in Duluth for the judge's decision on whether
to extend his order until the case could go to trial.
   ``I was scared either way,'' she said. ``I was scared to go
through with the abortion procedure and scared that I wouldn't be
able to legally go through with it.''
   When word arrived that the judge had not extended the order, the
abortion was performed before her husband could file an appeal. She
was two months pregnant.
   ``It's hard enough to have an abortion,'' she said. ``It's even
harder to go through with it when the world knows about it and you
have to go out on the street afterwards.''
   At times, Anderson, 34, has doubted whether he did the right
thing.
   ``I did what I thought was the right thing to do,'' he said. ``I
oppose abortion because of my religious beliefs and because I have
always thought abortion was bad.''
   After all the public attention, he said he and his wife want to
put the episode behind them.
   ``I wish it had never happened,'' he said. ``I want to forget
about the whole thing and put it in the past.''
</TEXT>
