<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Taktsis     08-28 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Taktsis,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Novelist Costas Taktsis Found Strangled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Author Costas Taktsis, whose novel ``The
Third Wedding Wreath'' won international acclaim after he published
it himself, was found strangled in his home, police said Sunday. He
was 61.
   Taktsis apparently had been dead for at least 48 hours when his
naked body was found Saturday evening, a police spokesman said. The
house in the seedy Kolonos district of Athens had been ransacked
and a video recorder was missing, said the spokesman, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Taktsis, born in the northern city of Salonica, studied law
before becoming a full-time writer and translator. He wrote ``The
Third Wedding Wreath'' in 1962 and had it published at his own
expense.
   The book, which was written in the first person, tells the story
of Nitsa, an Athenian woman who survived World War II and the Greek
civil war through her resilience and caustic sense of humor.
   Ignored by Greek critics, the book sold few copies until it was
translated into English in 1968. It then won enthusiastic reviews
that praised Taktsis' humorous insight and lively picture of
middle-class Athenian life.
   Taktis also was known for his translations of ancient Greek
plays into modern Greek, often for experimental performances by
Athenian theater groups.
   His most recent book was ``Grandmother Athina,'' a collection of
essays and short stories about the Greek capital inspired by
memories of his grandmother.
</TEXT>
