<DOCNO> AP880828-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-88 1127EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan     08-28 0688</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan,0709</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Leaders Map Post-Zia Strategy, British Press Reports
Sabotage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IQBAL JAFFERY</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUETTA, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Left-wing opposition leaders began
mapping new strategies Sunday for sharing political power after the
death of President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq.
   Leading British newspapers, meanwhile, reported that Pakistan
concluded sabotage was to blame for the Aug. 17 plane crash that
killed Zia, the U.S. ambassador to Pakistan and many of the
country's top generals.
   The Sunday Times of London said Pakistani officials believe Zia
was killed by an international conspiracy involving Pakistani
activists in Britain. It said the government wants to question five
Pakistani nationals in Britain. The newspaper gave no attribution.
   The Sunday Telegraph quoted unidentified sources in Washington
as saying the Pakistani investigation concluded the plane was shot
down by a missile. The newspaper did not say what kind of missile
was involved or who fired it.
   The Observer newspaper said Pakistani officials were convinced
India's intelligence service was to blame. It quoted unidentified
high-level Pakistani sources.
   The Pakistani government has not made any official statements on
the cause of the crash, although individual officials have said
they believe it was sabotage. U.S. and British diplomats in
Islamabad, the Pakistani capital, have said they are not aware of
any initial conclusions in the Pakistani inquiry.
   In Pakistan, the Movement for the Restoration of Democracy, a
nine-party opposition alliance, planned to meet Sunday and Monday
in the southern city of Karachi to plot strategy.
   On Saturday in the western city of Quetta, an estimated 20,000
opposition supporters waved banners and chanted anti-Zia slogans as
speakers called for a neutral caretaker government to guide the
nation to a return to civilian rule in general elections scheduled
for Nov. 16.
   Several of Zia's civilian backers have been appointed to a
caretaker Cabinet.
   As chief of the army, Zia shared power with a civilian
government for only three of his eleven years in power. But his
replacement as army chief, Gen. Aslam Beg, said last week the
military's role would be to ensure an orderly transition to
democracy.
   Leaders at the rally praised Beg's intentions but called on
Acting President Ghulam Ishaq Khan to replace the caretaker
government with ``neutral people'' until the November polls.
   ``If Ishaq Khan wants peace and harmony in the country and
cooperation of the political leaders, he should immediately do away
with the present ministers,'' said Abdul Wali Khan, leader of the
Socialist Awami National Party.
   ``Unless this is done, no politicans will extend any
continuation of Zia's dictatorship, a rule of tyranny and
oppression which lasted 11 years,'' Wali Khan said.
   He called on Ishaq Khan to come out squarely for party-based
elections instead of non-party polls ordered by Zia before his
death.
   Ishaq Khan, a former Senate chairman, told reporters at his
first news conference he would follow the Constitution, which
reconizes a party-based parliamentary system.
   But he said he would let the Supreme Court rule on opposition
petitions to open the November elections to all comers.
   Opposition alliance leaders said they expected to win seats in a
new national assembly, but there are no reliable figures in
Pakistan on party memberships.
   The alliance's largest member, Benazir Bhutto's Pakistan
People's Party, is considered the nation's largest party. But the
party and its alliance partners boycotted the only elections held
under Zia's rule, in 1985, because candidates were allowed to run
only as individuals.
   The Sunday Times said that because Pakistan has no extradition
treaty with Britain, it was approaching the British Embassy in
Islamabad with a request that five Pakistanis suspected of a role
in the plane crash be sent back ``as a special favor.''
   The newspaper said at least three previous attempts to
assassinate Zia involved Pakistanis in Britain. It identified six
Pakistanis who it said were either involved in the attempts or
wanted Zia dead.
   The newspaper said it spoke to five of them. Four denied
involvement in Zia's death while the fifth, who admitted being
involved in previous attempts, said he could not comment, the paper
said.
   Three of the five said they would have killed the president
willingly, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
