<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfRdp     08-28 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0648</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Claims Cease-Fire Violations by Iran
^With AM-Gulf Talks, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said Sunday that Iranian troops fired
shots and set up new radar and observation posts last week in
violation of a 9-day-old truce in the Persian Gulf war.
   Iran accused Iraq of undermining the peace talks in Geneva by
claiming sovereignty over the disputed Shatt-al-Arab waterway and
said the talks may drag on for years.
   The commander of the U.N. observer forces monitoring the truce
said the cease-fire was holding but that more time was needed to
finish plotting the exact location of the front line.
   The official Iraqi News Agency said more than a dozen Iranian
violations were reported to the U.N. peacekeepers between Tuesday
and Friday. Neither Iran nor the observer force commented on the
claims.
   In the northern region of Kurdistan, the Iranians set up two
radar positions manned by three Iranian officers, not far from
Iraqi troops, the agency said. It said ``appropriate measures were
taken to eliminate the two positions and push the enemy back'' but
did not elaborate.
   At the southern end of the front, Iranian soldiers fired shots
but U.N. observers intervened to ``stop the Iranian violations and
returned two advancing Iranians to their positions,'' the agency
said.
   In other parts of the front the Iranians set up barricades,
fired a machine gun, flew helicopters near Iraqi positions, and set
up other radar and observation posts, the agency said.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in
Cyprus, quoted Deputy Foreign Minister Javad Mansouri as saying
Iraq ``continues to have designs on Iran's territorial integrity.''
   IRNA quoted Mansouri as saying the Iraqi delegation in Geneva
``is underming the talks by bringing up irrelevant and
objectionable topics, such as Iraq's claim of sovereignty of the
Arvand river,'' Iran's name for the Shatt-al-Arab.
   He stressed that Tehran considers the 1975 Algiers Treaty, which
defined the border between the two countries, as valid. The treaty
granted Iran control of the eastern half of the waterway, which is
Iraq's only outlet to the sea.
   Iraqi President Saddam Hussein, who considered the treaty a
humiliation for Baghdad, tore up the accord during a televised
speech in September 1980.
   Mansouri said the negotiations in Geneva were going so slowly
that they might ``drag on for years to come.''
   In Baghdad, the head of the peacekeeping force, Maj. Gen. Slavko
Jovic of Yugoslavia, told a news conference that ``the cease-fire
is operational. The situation along the border is generally calm.
   ``Some minor problems and questions we are resolving through
negotiations, and enjoying very good help through the understanding
of both parties,'' Jovic said.
   He refused to say what the minor problems were, but indicated
there had been no confirmed major violations of the cease-fire that
took hold Aug. 20.
   Jovic said an Iraqi report last week that an Iranian sniper
killed an Iraqi soldier was ``unconfirmed,'' but was being
investigated.
   He said the roughly 300 U.N. observers on the ground were in the
process of determining the positions held by both sides when
fighting halted in the nearly 8-year-old war.
   Under a plan of action set out by U.N. Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar, withdrawal to the pre-war border is due at a
later stage.
   Defining the border is a key factor in the current peace talks
between Iranian and Iraqi leaders.
   Jovic confirmed the death of a Danish major, identified by other
sources as Steen Preben-Andersen. U.N. officials said the major
apparently suffered a heat stroke along the sweltering central
front Aug. 23 at about 2 p.m. and was quickly hospitalized by the
Iraqis.
   The Iraqi agency, INA, said Preben-Andersen's body was taken to
Baghdad airport on Sunday on its way back to Denmark.

</TEXT>
