<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Retreat     08-28 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Retreat,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Berkshire Village Dubious About Becoming Presidential Retreat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRUDY TYNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TYRINGHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Folks who live in Michael Dukakis'
favorite summer spot are divided over how well their isolated
hamlet in a valley of the Berkshire Hills would bear up if it
becomes a presidential retreat.
   ``I'm too old and our little town is too peaceful for this,''
said Carolyn Canon, 77, a Republican resident of the town the
Democratic presidential nominee and state governor has declared his
preferred place for respites from politics.
   Tyringham has no school. Christmas lights still adorn the fire
station. The Appalachian Trail cuts through the center of the
hamlet with barely a notice.
   Dukakis' hideaway is a modest one-story white ranch, with a
small guest cottage and backyard pool, on the edge of the hamlet
that has about as many year-around residents as there are days in
the year. It belongs to his father-in-law, Harry Ellis Dickson,
associate conductor of the Boston Pops.
   ``I don't really think we have anything to worry about,'' said
Betty Jean Cernik, the town tax collector for 27 years. ``It's a
long way from Tyringham to the White House. But the majority of
people in town dread the thought of him being here and the tourists
and Secret Service and all.''
   Tacked on the wall next to the postal boxes in a corner of the
town library _ beneath a ``Thank You'' note to townsfolk from a
recent widow _ was a local newspaper story about Tyringham's
possibilities as a presidential retreat. The clipping enlivened the
morning for some of librarian Irma Clark's postal customers.
   ``Oh, my God,'' said one elderly women, whose family has lived
in the valley for six generations. ``Tyringham will be on the map
and it's starting already. Don't you dare put my name in the
paper.''
   ``All I can say is here goes another voter for (Republican
contender George) Bush,'' said a young mother rushing out the door
with her mail, who also declined to give her name.
   ``I just can't understand the reaction,'' said Mary Hale, who as
chairman of the board of selectmen also serves as chief of
Tyringham's four-member part-time police force. ``People are just
being ridiculous.
   ``He's been coming here for years and it never bothered them
before. I run meetings with him every month in Boston and he always
asks about the town and says how much he wished he was there,''
said Ms. Hale, who is also president of the Massachusetts Municipal
Association.
   ``He is a dear person, a lovely person and an asset to the
village,'' she said. ``I'm sure no one even noticed the other
presidents who stayed here.''
   The 249-year-old town is no stranger to the rich and famous.
Presidents Grover Cleveland and William Taft were summer residents
and Mark Twain gave the library a complete set of his books after
spending the summer of 1903 here. Nat King Cole's widow is a
longtime resident, as are a few soap opera stars, television
producers and writers.
   Dukakis is a familiar sight jogging on back roads and riding
around in a beat-up Dodge, said dairy farmer Charles Slater, 71.
   ``He comes here for privacy and I let him have it. There's no
fanfare with the guy. People respect privacy here and don't make no
big fuss,'' said Slater, whose Crystal Brooks farm has been in his
family for eight generations.
   ``I just hope it's not like it was with the queen,'' said his
wife, Elizabeth, recalling the impact Queen Wilhelmina of the
Netherlands had on the neighboring town of Lee when she and her
family fled there to escape the Nazis during World War II.
   ``The town was overrun by the FBI and the other men President
Roosevelt sent to guard her,'' Mrs. Slater said. ``You couldn't
even get into the stores to shop.''
</TEXT>
