<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SouthAsia-Nuclear     08-28 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Asia-Nuclear,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Restraint Seen in South Asian Nuclear Arms Race</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release 6 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The long-smouldering nuclear arms race in
South Asia is being restrained by strategic and political factors,
opening the way for limited non-proliferation arrangements
involving India, Pakistan and possibly China, according to a Senate
study published Sunday.
   The report by the Senate Foreign Relations Committee staff
concludes that despite their advanced atomic energy programs,
neither India nor Pakistan has chosen to undertake an overt nuclear
weapons project.
   The study says India, which detonated a nuclear explosive device
in 1974, leads Pakistan in nuclear expertise, command of nuclear
weapons technology and access to fissionable material.
   The report concludes that India could produce a dozen to 18
nuclear weapons a year and that Pakistan is capable of
manufacturing only one to three such weapons annually.
   Prepared by Peter W. Galbraith, a South Asia expert on the
committee staff, the report says both Pakistan and India see
strategic disadvantages in the general spread of nuclear weapons in
South Asia.
   It says this ``provides an incentive for each to take steps to
keep the region free of nuclear weapons.''
   ``For Pakistan, a subcontinental arms race is a race it's sure
to lose,'' the report said. ``Pakistan cannot match India's nuclear
production capabilities and would face annihilation by India in a
hypothetical nuclear exchange between the two.''
   For its part, India has little to fear from a conventionally
armed Pakistan but that ``a nuclear-armed Pakistan could inflict
major damage,'' the study said.
   It noted that prominent Pakistani politicians have adopted
positions against nuclear weapons. The report said there is no
indication that the Aug. 17 plane explosion that killed President
Mohammed Zia ul-Haq will produce any change in Pakistan's nuclear
policies.
   U.S. relations with Pakistan and India often have been strained
over nuclear issues, although Washington's concern over nuclear
proliferation at times has been overshadowed by attention to other
regional problems.
   ``The successful implementation of the Geneva accords for a
Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan may again make non-proliferation
the top U.S. priority in the region,'' the report said.
   India's concern about China's nuclear arsenal must be taken into
account in any comprehensive arrangement to keep South Asia free of
nuclear weapons, the study said.
   ``A nuclear weapons free zone that included parts of China and
the Indian Ocean as well as South Asia might be achievable,'' it
said.
   The report says both India and Pakistan have ample means to
deliver nuclear warheads to their targets, and that India has the
advantage over its neighbor.
   The study notes that India recently successfully test-fired a
short-range surface-to-surface missile called the Prithvi which may
be capable of carrying a nuclear warhead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
