<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-88 1240EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Burma Bjt   08-28 0733</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma, Bjt,0759</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Form Illegal Union, Thousands of Prisoners Released</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Activist students, emboldened by massive
student-led demonstrations that toppled a president, moved Sunday
toward a more public stance by forming a union in defiance of the
law.
   Authorities released 4,806 prisoners from the Insein Jail north
of the capital two days after a riot and mass escape left at least
57 people dead and 106 injured, state-run Rangoon radio said.
   Large breakouts were reported last week at three other prisons
in Burma.
   The radio said those released Sunday from Insein, which holds
about 10,000 prisoners, included people whose trials were
continuing or who had less than a year's time to serve.
   Local residents gave some of the freed prisoners clothes, small
packets of rice and bus fare home, the radio said. Other prisoners
walked into Rangoon and asked people on the street for money to
return home.
   On Saturday, authorities freed 655 prisoners from Insein for
good conduct or because they were nearing the end of their
sentences.
   About 50,000 students gathered at Rangoon University and learned
of the formation of the All-Burma Students Union and a temporary
14-member executive committee chaired by student leader Min Ko
Naing.
   ``Our fight for democracy is not yet over. ... We want
democracy, right of association and we will continue to resist any
government that will deprive us of these rights,'' Min Ko Naing
told the crowd.
   Burma's students entered national politics in the early 1920s
and were active against British colonial rule.
   Shortly after former leader Ne Win seized power in 1962 he
crushed a student rebellion at Rangoon University, ordered the
student union building destroyed and banned student unions.
   Underground student unions began to operate about three years
ago and masked students were in the vanguard of anti-government
demonstrations in March, June and July.
   Sunday's events appeared to indicate the students were moving
more into the open. But the identities of the executive committee
members were not revealed, and little was known about the union
leader although his name has been on anti-government pamphlets in
recent weeks.
   Min Ko Naing told the crowd of students that after democracy was
won, a national student convention would elect a permanent union
leadership.
   Government-run newspapers began to circulate again Sunday,
carrying pictures and stories of anti-government demonstrations.
   Employees demanding press freedom had forced all six government
newspapers, four in the Burmese language and two in English, to
close for three days.
   ``We agreed to return to work on promises by the authorities
that we can now write freely,'' said an editorial assistant of one
newspapers.
   Although the newspapers played down reports of anti-government
agitation, Burmese readers noted that such articles and photographs
could never have appeared in the press in past decades.
   A Western diplomat in Rangoon said that although the capital was
relatively quiet Sunday, food stocks were reduced and people had to
go to more than one market to get enough food.
   Pro-democracy strikes halted all rail service and reduced bus
service last week. Union Burma Airways, which earlier last week
halted domestic flights, suspended international service on Friday,
the diplomat said on condition of anonymity.
   The strikes also closed oil refineries, crippled factories and
left foreign ships waiting at Rangoon's river port, officials said
Saturday.
   The turmoil in Burma began July 23 when 77-year-old Ne Win
resigned and the ruling Burma Socialist Program Party chose
hardliner Sein Lwin as his replacement.
   Mass student-led demonstrations followed. Troops shot unarmed
protestors, but the rallies continued until Sein Lwin quit and was
replaced as president Aug. 19 by civilian lawyer Maung Maung.
Rallies have been peaceful since then.
   In Dhaka, Bangladesh, thousands of people converged on a
southern sea resort after hearing Ne Win was hiding there, a
newspaper said Sunday.
   The Bangladesh Observer, an independent English-language daily,
reported Ne Win crossed into Bangladesh and was staying at a motel
in Coxs Bazar, about 185 miles south of Dhaka.
   It said thousands of people who rushed to the motel, hoping to
catch a glimpse of the former dictator, were told by police he was
not there or anywhere in town.
   Another Bangladesh newspaper, the mass-circulation Ittefaq, said
the former ruler and a 26-member entourage had taken shelter at a
Buddhist monastery in eastern Bangladesh.
   The Foreign Office in Dhaka dismissed both reports as ``baseless
rumors.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
