<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Plane Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0693,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Three Jets Crash At Air Show; Up To 31 Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with 31 feared dead, details. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMSTEIN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Italian air force jets
collided and crashed during an air show at a U.S. military base
Sunday, and a state government official said up to 31 people were
feared dead.
   A police spokesman in nearby Kaiserslautern said at least 100
people were injured at Ramstein Air Base, some of them seriously.
One of the airplanes plowed into the crowd on the ground,
eyewitnesses said.
   ``We fear that in all likelihood 30 or 31 people are dead,''
Rhineland-Palatinate state government spokesman Hennes Schreiner
said in a telephone interview.
   Schreiner said state governor Bernhard Vogel immediately headed
to the base 60 miles southwest of Frankfurt to help supervise joint
German-American rescue efforts.
   Base spokesman Doug Moore said the dead included the three
pilots, and ``those dead on the ground are a mix of civilian and
military.''
   Moore said investigators were still piecing together the
sequence of events. He said it was not certain whether all three
planes collided at once or whether two first hit each other and the
third later become involved. All three planes crashed, he said.
   Bernd Nagel, a spokesman for Rhineland-Palatinate state, said
eyewitnesses reported that one of the planes plowed directly into
the crowd of spectators.
   Willi Hollaender, a police spokesman in Kaiserslautern, told the
AP that at least 100 people were injured, ``several of them
seriously.''
   The planes involved were of the type Airmacchi MB 339A,
according to Hollaender. He said eyewitnesses reported that one of
the planes crashed into the crowd.
   Officials said the planes belonged to the ``Frecce Tricolori''
flying team of the Italian air force.
   Hesse State radio in Frankfurt said that about 15 people had
received ``serious burns.''
</TEXT>
