<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PuyallupsSettlement     08-28 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Puyallups Settlement,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Puyallup Indians Vote To Accept Land Claim Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Puyallup Indian Tribe has voted
overwhelmingly to end years of negotiations and accept a $162
million offer in return for giving up claim to one-time reservation
land that includes parts of Tacoma.
   ``The agreement works to everyone's benefit,'' Gabriel Landry of
the Puyallup Tribal Council said after Saturday's 319-162 vote.
   A legal battle for the disputed land ``might've taken 20 or 30
years,'' and would be expensive, Landry added. He said he also
believed Puyallups would've been subjected to an anti-Indian
backlash if they'd taken the various government bodies involved to
court.
   At issue is who owns what within the boundaries of the old
reservation, which includes parts of downtown Tacoma, the city's
northeast side and the Tacoma Tideflats, now home of the booming
Port of Tacoma, the nation's 16th largest port.
   Treaties dating from the 1850s gave the Puyallups a reservation
of about 18,000 acres. Over the years, holdings dwindled as land
allotted to individual members was sold in what tribal historians
say often were shady or fraudulent deals.
   Two decades ago, about all that was left was a 35-acre cemetery.
But tribal activists fought the state and local governments over
treaty rights and land claims, and vigorous enrollment efforts
boosted the tribe's membership from a low point of about 400.
Today, the tribe has about 1,500 members.
   In 1984, the U.S. Supreme Court let stand a ruling giving the
tribe title to 12 acres of former Puyallup River bed. That opened
the question of whether the tribe could lay claim to more land.
   The settlement is to include about $77 million from the federal
government, $21 million from the state and the balance from the
city of Tacoma, the Port of Tacoma and private property owners,
including Union Pacific Railroad.
   The next challenge is to get appropriations from Congress and
from the state Legislature to help finance the package, said U.S.
Rep. Norm Dicks, D-Wash.
   He said he would introduce legislation in the House and Sen. Dan
Inouye, D-Hawaii, chairman of the Select Committee on Indians,
would introduce the legislation in the Senate.
   The proposal may not reach Congress until next year, Dicks added.
   The tribe voted 118-102 to reject a proposed $140 million
settlement in February 1986. Had the tribe rejected this proposal,
it would have gone to court to claim the land.
   ``Years of litigation would have been enormously expensive and
somebody loses,'' Dicks said. ``This way, both the community and
the tribe can win and I think that's better for everyone.''
   Frank Wright Jr., administrative manager for the tribe, has said
he sees the settlement as an opportunity to strengthen the tribe
economically and provide a better future for its members. He was
ousted as tribal council chairman after the earlier proposal was
rejected.
   Lynn Anderson, port spokeswoman, said the decision will give
private landowners clear title and help confirm exactly who owns
what, and allow work with the tribe on issues of fisheries and
development.
   The complex package promises a number of thing to the tribe,
including $20,000 in cash to each adult tribal member, a variety of
economic development programs, 900 acres of land, job training, a
substance-abuse treatment center, fish enhancement programs and a
$22 million permanent tribal trust fund.
   Some members remained strongly opposed to the deal, but Landry
said he thought a combination of the length of time involved in the
negotiations and the fact that the new proposal was better helped
persuade members to approve it.
   ``People are tired of hearing it. And they really do see the
advantages,'' he said.
   While ``there's no way we can put a value on the amount of loss
that we've had, this gives us an opportunity to put our tribe on
the map,'' Landry said. ``I'm looking foward. I'm not looking back
at the injustices we've suffered. ''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
