<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joan Rivers, who's rarely at a loss for words,
is writing another book about herself.
   Rivers' new book will cover her career climb, including her
stint as a late-night talk show host, and her husband Edgar's
suicide, New York Magazine reports in its Aug. 29 issue.
   ``It will be a real woman's story _ the tale of an astonishing
actress and comedienne who is slowly building her life,'' said
Susan Kamil, an editor at Random House.
   According to the magazine, Random House paid $400,000 for the
book, which it plans to publish in 1990. Richard Meryman, who
worked with Rivers on her first book ``Enter Talking'' in 1986,
will also collaborate on this one.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Malcolm Jamal Warner of ``The Cosby Show''
and Peter De Luise, Holly Robinson and Dustin Nguyen of ``21 Jump
Street'' are among 16 young television and film stars who have
posed for a calendar that warns against mixing drinking and driving.
   The entertainers cooperated with the Los Angeles chapter of
Mothers Against Drunk Drivers, which said the calendar, aimed at
teen-agers, is a first of its kind.
   ``If it makes people think twice about getting into a car drunk,
I think it's great,'' Nguyen said in a telephone interview from
Vancouver, Canada, where he is filming a guest spot on ``Danger
Bay.''
   He added: ``I think it's definitely going to have an effect.''
   Nguyen posed with Holly Robinson and Peter De Luise on the hood
of De Luise's own 1955 Chevrolet.
   The actors and actresses also provided statements that will be
used in captions under their photos.
   Money raised from sales of the $7.95 calendar will be used to
develop an educational program for junior high school students,
according to Betty Johnson, director of development and community
affairs for the Los Angeles chapter of MADD. Twenty thousand copies
of the calendar will be printed initially, she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Quentin Burdick is recovering well
from colon surgery he underwent last week and is ``very anxious''
to leave the hospital, according to an aide.
   The North Dakota Democrat doesn't like hospitals, Jean
Brodshaug, Burdick's press secretary, said in a telephone interview
from Washington.
   Doctors say Burdick, 80, should be able to leave the Bethesda
Naval Hospital in Maryland by midweek, Brodshaug said Saturday.
   Surgeons removed 18 inches of Burdick's colon Thursday after an
earlier exam detected a cancerous polyp in the colon. Burdick had
three of the growths removed from his colon last month; tests
showed one of them was malignant.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Paul Newman will portray the late
Earl Long in a movie about the Louisiana governor's romance with
former striptease artist Blaze Starr, according to a writer who
helped Starr with her autobiography.
   Ron Shelton, writer and director of this summer's hit movie
``Bull Durham,'' will direct the movie, to be titled ``Blaze,''
Huey Perry said.
   ``We've been working with Ron since 1981 and sometimes I thought
the story of Blaze would never reach the screen,'' Perry said.
   Last week, Shelton told a Baltimore newspaper that the movie has
a budget of $50 million to $60 million.
   Filming is expected to take place next spring, ``probably in
Louisiana,'' Perry said, adding that the role of Starr has not been
cast yet.
   Starr, who lives in Oakland, Md., told The (Huntington)
Herald-Dispatch Friday that she was visiting her mother in
Wilsondale, Mingo County, last week when she heard that Touchstone
Pictures had agreed to the deal. She said she's excited that Newman
will play Long, who died in 1960 at age 65.
   The movie will focus on the part of Starr's 1974 autobiography
that discusses her love affair in the late 1950s with the populist
governor known as ``Ole Earl.'' The affair took place while Starr
was a stripper on Bourbon Street in New Orleans before she moved to
Baltimore and gained a national reputation.
   Long left Starr $50,000 in his will, but his widow prevented her
from collecting the money. Starr, 56, is retired from the
striptease business and makes jewelry that she sells at craft shows.
</TEXT>
