<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cambodia     08-28 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cambodia,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Says Vietnam Trying To Maintain Hold On Cambodia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet and Chinese diplomats Sunday began talks
on ending Cambodia's civil war, and a Chinese government newspaper
said Vietnam was trying to maintain control of Cambodia after it
ends its 10-year occupation.
   The commentary, prominently displayed on the front-page of the
People's Daily, accused Vietnam of ``playing games'' with
international attempts to bring peace to Cambodia.
   The nationally televised evening news said the talks between
Soviet Deputy Foreign Minister Igor Rogachev and his Chinese
counterpart opened Sunday morning.
   It showed footage of the two sides sitting down at a long
conference table but did not give any details about the meeting.
The talks, which are closed to foreign reporters, are expected to
last a week.
   Rogachev said Saturday he thought a breakthrough was at hand.
   Neither China nor the Soviet Union are direct participants in
the Cambodian conflict, but Moscow gives financial support to
Vietnam and China supports the three-party resistance coalition
headed by Prince Norodom Sihanouk.
   China wants the Soviet Union to put pressure on Vietnam to
withdraw all its 120,000 troops from Cambodia at an early date,
Foreign Ministry spokesman Jin Guihua said last week.
   A settlement on the Cambodian question would remove the last
obstacle to normalized Chinese-Soviet relations and pave the way
for a summit meeting between Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev and
Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping.
   The People's Daily editorial reiterated China's stand that ``the
key to a political settlement of the Cambodian question is the
withdrawal of Vietnamese troops.''
   Hanoi in May agreed to withdraw 50,000 troops this year and the
remainder by 1990.
   But the editorial said: ``Vietnam's so-called `troop withdrawl
by 1990' is but a lie.''
   It recalled that in the past Vietnamese withdrawals amounted to
nothing more than troop rotations. It also said some Vietnamese
soldiers were discharged and told to settle in Cambodia to help in
the ``Vietnamization'' of the country.
   The editorial also accused Vietnam of delaying its troop
withdrawal by using worldwide concern that the Khmer Rouge, which
slaughtered hundreds of thousands of people during its 1975-1978
rule, might again gain power.
   ``The international community must not only guard against the
Khmer Rouge gaining power but even more must firmly oppose the
faction of Hun Sen gaining sole power,'' the newspaper warned.
   Prime Minister Hun Sen leads the Vietnamese-installed government
in Phnom Penh.
   Chinese Communist Party chief Zhao Ziyang, in a meeting with
visiting Japanese Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita on Friday, issued
the same warning.
   ``The more immediate danger is that Vietnam is trying by every
possible means to legalize the puppet regime in Cambodia,'' he said.
   The People's Daily editorial concluded with a call for continued
international pressure on Vietnam to leave Cambodia and allow the
Cambodian people to set up their own government.
   China supports a four-party coalition government made up of the
three resistance factions and Hun Sen's government and headed by
resistance leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
