<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     08-28 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rocket Attack on Kabul Airport Damaged Plane, Runways</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least one transport plane may have
been destroyed and some runways damaged when Afghan guerrillas
rocketed Kabul airport for more than two hours, Western diplomats
said Sunday.
   The official Soviet news agency Tass said four people were
killed and 17 injured during the attack Saturday, which the
diplomats said lasted more than two hours.
   It was not known if the attack was the same as that reported
Saturday on an unidentified part of Kabul, in which Tass said four
were killed.
   The Western diplomats, quoting a dispatch from their embassy in
the Afghan capital, said more than 20 rockets hit the
civilian-military airport Saturday afternoon and early evening.
   It said helicopters and jet fighters scrambled but several large
aircraft remained on the ground.
   ``A Western diplomat saw several rockets hit directly in front
of the old airport control tower, about 200 yards to the north, and
then saw three rockets impact directly between the main runways,
apparently damaging at least one of them,'' the dispatch said.
   The diplomats spoke to journalists and provided the dispatch on
condition of anonymity.
   The dispatch said damage to aircraft was not confirmed visually,
but the airport remained closed Saturday night.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in December 1979, and an
estimated 100,000 troops have been helping the Marxist government
fight the Moslem rebels.
   The guerrillas have stepped up attacks on the capital and
provincial centers since Red Army troops began withdrawing from
Afghanistan May 15 under a U.N.-brokered accord.
   Diplomats said Saturday's attack appeared to come from only a
few miles southeast of the airport. It indicated the rebels had
penetrated the heavy security ringing the city.
   Reports from the war zones indicate the rebels hold two Afghan
provincial capitals and have besieged at least two more.
   Afghan leader Najib said in a speech to the country's national
assembly Saturday that his government planned to declare
``coalition or neutral zones'' on the basis of negotiations with
``armed opposition groups.''
   The rebels had no immediate reaction. Guerrilla leaders have
refused to negotiate with the Marxists, whom they see as Soviet
puppets.
   The seven-party guerrilla alliance, based in Peshawar, Pakistan,
announced plans of its own Sunday to hold elections in refugee
camps and ``liberated areas'' inside Afghanistan.
   Winning candidates would form a legislative body under an
interim Cabinet named among guerrilla leaders last June.
   Rebel spokesman have said their government would set up soon in
Afghanistan but have given no dates. They said they hope to hold
elections early this fall.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
