<DOCNO> AP880828-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-88 1451EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SmokelessChicago Bjt   08-28 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smokeless Chicago, Bjt,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chicago Officials Declare Month-old Smoking Ban a Success</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PERKISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A month after the Windy City snuffed out smoking
in public places, sending smokers huffing to puff outside or in
designated areas, officials in the nation's third-largest city say
the ban is a success.
   ``If complaints are an efficient barometer of what's going on,
then the law is working,'' said Patrick Lenihan, deputy
commissioner for planning in the Department of Health. ``We haven't
heard too much about it.''
   But some restaurant operators say the ordinance, which forces
eateries to guarantee patrons a non-smoking area, has created
problems.
   ``It's costing us money because in order to keep a non-smoking
area, we have to keep waiters on the job rather than sending them
home and closing part of the restaurant,'' said Peter Tung, manager
of Trader Vic's.
   ``We're finding that at certain times some of our non-smoking
customers have to wait an extra five or 10 minutes,'' said William
Marquardt, vice president of the Berghoff restaurant. ``When that
happens there's some grumbling.''
   The law, which bans smoking in restaurants, stores, businesses,
airports, bus terminals, subway stations and taxis, took effect
July 25.
   But the City Council passed the ordinance without setting up a
mechanism to enforce the law, which calls for $25 to $100 fines,
and no one has been cited for violations.
   Lenihan said the Health Department and the Council are working
to set up regulations for enforcing the ordinance. Rules should be
on the books in about a month.
   Similar laws have been passed in New York, Los Angeles and other
cities around the country.
   ``We're finding that businesses, stores and restaurants are
trying to come into compliance with the law voluntarilly,'' Lenihan
said. ``In 90 percent of the cases the honor system is working.''
   ``Almost 75 percent of our customers are non-smokers so for them
the law is a plus,'' said Michael Cameron, general manager of
Michael Stuart's Restaurant. ``At least half the restaurant is
non-smoking and we're going to expand it.''
   Lenihan said the few complaints received by the Health
Department have been about small restaurants that have not stopped
their patrons from lighting up.
   Other complaints have come from passengers reporting taxi
drivers lighting up in their cabs.
   ``We've gotten a few of those, but not too many,'' said Patricia
Masters of the mayor's Office of Inquiry and Information. ``It's
been fairly quiet.''
   Some cabbies said they would keep on puffing despite the ban.
   ``Some laws I obey and some I don't'' said Watson Rembert. ``I
still smoke but I just don't do it in front of the police. If I
want to smoke, I'll light up because I'm a smoker.''
   On the corporate front, Mary Jean Houde, a spokeswoman for Sears
Roebuck and Co., said there had been no complaints in the company's
8,000-worker headquarters since the ban took effect.
   Sears placed ``no smoking'' signs in the lobby of the Sears
Tower and also put them in bathrooms and conference rooms, she said.
   Ms. Houde declined to say how much Sears spent to comply with
the new law.
   ``Prior to the law taking effect we had designated employee
lounges as either smoking or non-smoking,'' Ms. Houde said. ``We're
complying and nobody seems to be upset about it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
