<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Portugal-Fire 1stLd-Writethru a0679 08-28 0722</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Portugal-Fire, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0679,0743</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lisbon Blaze Fuels Fears Of Other Such Disasters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2 grafs for 6th graf pvs, `Jose Ferreira de...' with
details of firefighting equipment. Picks up 7th pvs, `Sabado wrote
that...' SUBS 2 grafs for 11th graf pvs, `The flames swept...' with
details of damage. Picks up 12th pvs, `Fire officials say...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lisbon's biggest fire in two centuries
destroyed much of the old Moorish quarter in the heart of the city
and fueled fears that other such disasters may follow.
   Thursday's blaze reduced the historic 10-block Chiado shopping
district to smoldering ruins. Critics blamed the city's antiquated
firefighting equipment and lax safety rules.
   ``(What) Else Will Be Burned?'' asked the newsmagazine Sabado.
   Architect Tomas Taveira, who watched the hand-painted tile
facades go up in flames, said he saw ancient fire trucks crawling
towards the blaze an hour after it was reported at 3 a.m.
   ``Portugal has to look toward progress in a different way,''
Taveira said.
   Jose Ferreira de Matos, president of the Lisbon Shopowners
Association, called the outdated equipment ``shameful.''
   Some of the fire trucks _ which are at least 30 years old _ were
used in the Portuguese colonial wars in Africa in the 1960s and
early 1970s. About half of the 800 or so firefighters who battled
the blaze were volunteers from fire stations near Lisbon, who came
with equipment that was even older than the city's.
   Sabado wrote that the citizens of Lisbon long have sensed ``how
little is being done to avoid such disasters.''
   Reports said none of the old wood frame buildings in the area
had sprinkler systems, including the 19th century Armazens do
Grandela department store, where the blaze started. No one could
remember when fire officials last inspected the buildings.
   The city's media agreed it was ``a miracle'' only one man died
and 43 people were injured in the fire, which started before crowds
filled the popular area.
   The flames swept through the narrow streets with their specialty
shops and cafes, where artists, writers and musicians gathered.
Lawyers, whose offices were on fire, scurried down the slippery
streets carrying documents and were joined by fleeing residents
carrying cats, dogs and caged parakeets.
   The fire left 40 stores gutted, about 2,000 people jobless and
damages Ferreira de Matos estimated at $600 million.
   Fire officials say they don't know what caused the blaze, the
worst in the capital in 200 years, but news reports raised the
possibility of arson. Ferreira De Matos said firefighters were
victims of a bureaucracy that shows no concern for the welfare of
this city of 900,000.
   Jose Manuel Fernandes, writing in the weekly Expresso in
December, said Lisbon has been without direction or a coherent
urban plan since the death of Mayor Duarte Pacheco in 1948.
   Mayor Nuno Kruz Abecasis has presided over the city council for
10 of the 14 years since a 1974 leftist coup ended nearly half a
century of dictatorship in Portugal.
   As the country floundered after the revolution, the mayor came
under increasing criticism for leaving Lisbon prey to real estate
speculators, who ignored safety or architectural integrity.
   The Chiado neighborhood, which was completed in 1840, was a
symbol of Lisbon's literary and artistic past as well as haven for
its new artists and designers.
   Construction of the old quarter _ whose style was considered
revolutionary for its time _ was begun after a 1755 earthquake and
subsequent fire and tidal wave destroyed much of medieval Lisbon.
   ``It's a terrible shame that the fire had to strike the Chiado,
where young Portuguese were learning to take pride in the city's
heritage,'' said longtime resident Carole Gorton. Authorities said
it will be a year before reconstruction begins.
   French President Francois Mitterrand offered his country's aid
to repair the damage caused by ``the catastrophe that touched the
heart of Lisbon.''
   But critics have little confidence that officials will put such
aid to proper use. They say the money is likely to be frittered
away on projects that help only those who propose them.
   The state-owned Diaro de Noticias said in an editorial that the
Chiado fire must teach the people of Lisbon that they can no longer
indulge in their favorite pastime of ``deixar andar'' _ letting
things pass.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
