<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Escapee-Hostage     08-28 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Escapee-Hostage,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prison Escapee Commits Suicide During Standoff With Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal prison escapee who held his
estranged wife's boyfriend in a closet for more than two days and
later took the woman hostage killed himself early Sunday after a
12-hour standoff, officials said.
   Both hostages escaped without injury shortly after electricity
and gas to the house were shut off, the Multnomah County Sheriff's
Department said.
   Later, Herbert Lamar Weeks, 47, was found dead in the garage of
the house, an apparent victim of carbon monoxide poisoning,
according to a news release from the department.
   Weeks had kept police at bay since Saturday afternoon when
Weeks' wife, Marilyn, 40, telephoned a friend, who believed
something was wrong and notified the sheriff's department,
sheriff's spokesman Bart Whalen said.
   Deputy U.S. Marshal Shaun Means said Weeks had tied Mrs. Weeks'
boyfriend, identified by sheriff's deputies as Roddy Bergsma, 47,
and placed him in a closet Thursday. Mrs. Weeks apparently came
home Saturday afternoon and also was held against her will, Means
said.
   Sheriff's spokesman Jim Davis said a divorce had been pending
between Weeks and his wife.
   While a deputy was sent to the Weeks' residence, a sheriff's
dispatcher telephoned the house and Weeks told her he was heavily
armed and had a bomb.
   Nine homes in a one-block area of the suburban east Portland
neighborhood were evacuated. No shots were fired during the
standoff, deputies said.
   ``There wasn't much more conversation beyond that,'' Whalen
said. ``There weren't any demands or anything. Fortunately, the
officer had not gotten there, so there was no confrontation.''
   Deputies tried unsuccessfully to persuade Weeks to leave the
house. At 2:30 a.m. utilities lines into the house were shut off;
12 minutes later, Mrs. Weeks and Bergsma escaped, deputies said.
   Means said he was unsure how the pair got away from Weeks.
   Weeks was listed as an escapee on Aug. 21 from Lompoc Federal
Penitentiary in Lompoc, Calif., where he had been serving two
consecutive five-year terms, deputies said.
   He was convicted in U.S. District Court in Portland on Dec. 18
of interstate auto theft, altering vehicle identification numbers
and interstate fraud, Means said.
</TEXT>
