<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Winds Up Texas Tour, Plans Future Trips</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush spent a low-key Sunday
to wind up a four-day Texas visit that he called ``a good swing''
in this key election state that is his adopted home.
   The Republican presidential nominee attended an Astros baseball
game, church services and a memorial service for former Gov. Price
Daniel, a longtime friend.
   ``We've had a good swing,'' Bush said. ``We've had a good three
to four days here. We've got to work hard, but it's doable.''
   Bush's chief of staff, Craig Fuller, said the campaign was
``very excited'' about the reception Bush during the series of
campaign appearances that began Thursday. He mentioned in
particular the rally in Longview that drew about 2,500 people on
Thursday.
   Fuller said Dukakis' selection of Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen as a
running mate ``raises the stakes in Texas,'' which is worth 29 of
the 270 electoral college votes needed to win the presidency.
   Talking aboard Air Force Two, Fuller said Bush will continue to
stress defense in the coming week and paint Democratic rival
Michael Dukakis as weak on defense. Fuller said the campaign feels
that theme is going over well.
   Bush was heading Monday to St. Louis to tour an aerospace plant,
and then to Nashville, Tenn.
   Fuller said Bush would likely return to Texas by mid-September,
and in the meantime send surrogates and family members to work the
state.
   But Bush told reporters he wasn't engaging in any politics on
Sunday.
   The captain of his baseball team at Yale, Bush showed off his
pitching style by throwing out the first ball in the Astrodome as
the Houston Astros hosted the Pittsburgh Pirates.
   He told reporters he was there for ``pure R and R.''
   ``I know you won't believe it _ no politics today,'' he said
before donning an Astros jacket.
   Bush and his wife, Barbara, also attended the memorial service
in Austin for Daniel, who died Thursday after suffering a stroke.
   Mrs. Bush told reporters aboard Air Force Two that Daniel, a
Democrat, and his wife were old family friends of the Bushes.
   ``They were friends _ a different party, but friends,'' she said.
   She said she and her husband met Daniel in 1953, introduced by
Bush's parents, and became friendly as fellow Texans. Bush's
father, Prescott, and Daniel had both served in the U.S. Senate.
   Earlier Sunday, Bush attended services at St. Martin's Episcopal
Church near the Houston hotel complex where he maintains an
official address, and had lunch at Molina's Mexican restaurant,
owned by old family friends.
</TEXT>
