<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-28 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Drenches Atlantic Coast, Tornadoes Hit North Carolina</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Storms drenched the lower half of the Atlantic coast on Sunday,
with tornadoes spawned by Tropical Storm Chris hitting three North
Carolina counties.
   The tropical storm was downgraded to a tropical depression late
Sunday after it moved ashore near Charleston, S.C. Showers and
thunderstorms were over much of South Carolina, eastern Georgia and
western North Carolina. Showers also extended across central
Virginia to New Jersey.
   Damages were estimated as high as $1 million in North Carolina's
western central Iredell County, where two tornadoes touched down
Sunday, said Al Warlick, a spokesman for the state Department of
Crime Control and Public Safety. Sheriffs' dispatchers reported
tornado sightings in two other counties.
   Showers and a few thunderstorms extended from the lower Great
Lakes region to the southern high Plains early Sunday afternoon.
Thunderstorms produced heavy downpours in eastern New York.
   Showers and thunderstorms were also reported in southern
Florida. Showers and thunderstorms were widely scattered along the
central and western Gulf coast.
   Sunny skies prevailed from the upper Great Lakes through the
northern and central Plains to the northern and central Pacific
coast.
   Rainfall totals for the six-hour period ended at 2 p.m. EDT
included more than an inch and a half at Charleston, S.C.; more
than an inch at Beaufort, S.C.; more than eight-tenths of an inch
at Myrtle Beach, S.C.; and three quarters of an inch at Burlington,
Vt.
   Temperatures warmed into the 80s from south-central and eastern
Texas to Georgia and Florida. Readings were in the 80s across parts
of the middle and northern Atlantic Coast region and the upper Ohio
Valley.
   Cool weather prevailed across the rest of the nation east of the
Rockies, with readings mostly in the 60s and 70s. Temperatures in
the southwestern deserts were in the 90s or above 100 degrees.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 54
degrees at Las Vegas, N.M., to 101 degrees at Thermal, Calif., and
Yuma, Ariz. The nation's low Sunday morning was 30 degrees in West
Yellowstone, Mont.
   Monday's forecast was for showers and thunderstorms from the
central Gulf Coast to New England. Scattered showers and
thunderstorms were expected in the Southeast, the southern Plains,
the southern Rockies and the southern Plateau region. A few showers
were predicted for the Pacific Northwest and the upper Great Lakes
region. Sunny skies were forecast across the rest of the nation.
   High temperatures were expected to remain below 80 degrees from
New England across the Great Lakes region and the Ohio Valley into
the northern and central Plains, with afternoon highs in the 60s in
the Great Lakes region. Temperatures were expected to warm into the
lower 90s from south-central Texas to Florida and southern Georgia,
the 80s and lower 90s in the West, except upper 90s and above 100
degrees in the southwestern deserts and 70s along the Pacific Coast.
</TEXT>
