<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland 2ndLd-Writethru   08-28 0844</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0733,0868</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polish Leader Says Strikes May Lead To Government Shakeup</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to UPDATE with party meeting ending;
picks up 3rd pvs: Solidarity leader...; SUBS 6th graf pvs, `At
the...' to conform; picks up 7th pvs: Jaruzelski, the ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski on
Sunday called for national reconciliation and said top government
officials may be fired for failing to deal with the strongest wave
of strikes since 1981.
   But the two-day meeting of the Communist Party's Central
Committee ended without any immediate recommendations for changes
in Prime Minister Zbigniew Messner's government.
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa was slightly injured in a scuffle
with police. Troops blocked about 400 protesters trying to march on
the strikebound Lenin shipyard in Gdansk, where Walesa founded the
independent union federation in 1980.
   Talks ended a stubborn mine strike in the south, but 10 strikes
continued at ports, shipyards, factories and one mine. There were
no reports of police attempts to dislodge workers in occupation
strikes.
   Solidarity estimated about 8,500 people still were occupying
workplaces, striking for higher pay and legalization of Solidarity,
which was crushed with the imposition of martial law in 1981 and
outlawed in 1982.
   Jaruzelski, the Communist Party leader, severely criticized the
party's hand-picked government for failing to deal with building
economic and political tensions before they got out of control in
the strikes, which began Aug.16.
   He said the Central Committee would decide the fate of Messner's
government before Parliament meets in September. He also called for
for changes in the party leadership.
   Jaruzelski, whose closing speech was broadcast on television,
endorsed the idea of a discussion with representatives of striking
workers.
   ``We are invariably in favor of settling even the most difficult
questions by patience and dialogue. The hand remains
outstretched,'' he said. ``But there is no chance for an everything
or nothing attitude.''
   The government has not ruled out that such a forum might include
Walesa, who last held a high-level meeting with authorities in 1982
while interned after the imposition of martial law.
   At a news conference after the meeting, party spokesman Jerzy
Majka said Walesa was a possible candidate for such talks.
   The 230-member Central Committee endorsed continuing economic
and political reform with no ``halfway measures,'' but it condemned
``law-breaking and destruction,'' a reference to illegal strikes.
   Jaruzelski said the the government has a constant duty to keep
in touch with the population's feelings, and he criticized
officials for ``fanning out across the nation only after the fire
has started.''
   ``We are not used in the party to criticizing the government
from the rostrum of the Central Committee. That we have always done
in the family, silently,'' he said. ``Now we are finishing with
that practice.''
   But Jaruzelski's references to the opposition were milder.
   ``Our problems cannot be solved either by the weapon of strikes
or the means of coercion,'' he said. ``More than once in Polish
history, brother was pitted against brother. Time passed and then
they were standing side by side. It's about time that this road
prevails.
   ``There is no freedom without a sense of responsibility,'' he
said, echoing a favorite slogan of Solidarity: ``There is no
freedom without Solidarity.''
   Jaruzelski proposed transforming his ``consultative council''
into a ``council for national accord'' that presumably would seek
to forge areas of agreement between the government and opponents.
   Walesa left the Lenin shipyard Saturday to confer with advisers
about the possibility of talks with the government.
   When he tried to enter the cordoned-off shipyard Sunday morning,
a police officer tried to stop him, said a Walesa aide who spoke on
condition of anonymity. Walesa pulled away but lost a shoe and
scratched his hand when he climbed over the 7-foot fence into the
yard, the aide said.
   A Mass at the nearby St. Brygida's church drew about 10,000
worshipers who spilled into the square in front of the packed
church.
   ``From this place we have the right as free Poles to call for
freedom and the arrival of government authorities for roundtable
talks in the shipyard,'' the Rev. Henryk Jankowski, a Walesa
adviser, told worshipers.
   ``Let anyone who has a package of solutions for the current
situation sit at this table.''
   After the service, about 400 people tried to walk the five
blocks from the church to the shipyard entrance, but they were
blocked by massive lines of police in riot gear. The crowd
dispersed peacefully.
   The state-run PAP news agency said strikers decided to end the
10-day-old strike at the Jastrzebie mine in the southern town of
Jastrzebie at 6 p.m.
   The government and strikers earlier said talks were under way at
the mine, which was one of only two mines still on strike
nationwide, compared to 12 last week.
   Miners agreed to talk with management on local pay issues after
hearing rumors that Walesa would be speaking directly with the
government about legalizing Solidarity, said a strike spokeswoman
in Jastrzebie. Details on the tentative settlement were not
immediately available.
</TEXT>
