<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Latvians-Collaboration     08-28 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Latvians-Collaboration,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Latvians Defend Man Alleged To Be A Nazi Collaborator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the Latvian community are coming
to the defense of a man who government officials allege was a
member of a pro-Nazi police unit during World War II.
   Federal prosecutors initiated deportation proceedings last
Monday against Edgars Inde, 79, a retired factory worker who lives
in Minneapolis.
   In the civil lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court, authorities
allege that Inde belonged to the Latvian Auxiliary Police and
participated in killing unarmed Jews and other civilians during the
Nazi occupation of Latvia in 1941 and 1942. Latvia is now part of
the Soviet Union.
   ``He denies this, definitely,'' said the Rev. Modrus Gulbis of
Christ Latvian Evangelical Lutheran Church in Minneapolis, who has
spoken with Inde. ``As of this moment, I am quite convinced he is
innocent, although I would definitely want to hear the other side
of the story.''
   The suit alleges that Inde hid his participation in war crimes
when he came to the United States in 1949 and applied for
naturalization. He became a U.S. citizen in 1955.
   When contacted Monday, Inde denied he killed Jews. ``No, no, no,
no, no, no,'' he said.
   His lawyer, Ivars Berzins of New York City, has refused comment.
   Inde is a well-liked member of the 2,000-member Latvian
community and is active in theater.
   ``I can tell you, with all my heart, this is hard to take, that
... people might think all Latvians are pro-Nazis,'' said the Rev.
Janis Rozentals, a retired theologian from Lutheran Northwestern
Seminary.
   Many Latvian-Americans believe the Justice Department's Office
of Special Investigations, which investigates Nazi war criminals
living in the United States, has been overzealous in its
investigations of Latvians and other Baltic peoples.
   ``It seems like in the last five years, that's been the case,''
said Ojars Kalnins, spokesman for the American Latvian Association
in Rockville, Md. ``It seems like the Balts are being singled out
because that's the kind of evidence that OSI is getting from the
Soviets.''
   OSI Director Neal Sher said although a number of current
investigations involve Americans of Baltic origin, he didn't know
what percentage they constitute of the 600 cases under
investigation.
</TEXT>
