<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SubmarineWreck     08-28 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Submarine Wreck,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rescue Efforts Continue For Three Submariners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Divers searched for three missing sailors
Sunday after 21 others were removed from a sunken submarine on the
ocean floor in a dramatic day-long rescue operation.
   Officials said the captain of the submarine perished while
trying to save his men as the submarine sank Friday evening after
it was accidentally rammed by a Japanese tuna boat about three
miles off the port city of Callao.
   Three other crew members died and three are missing and presumed
dead, according to Peru's navy. It is believed the missing men are
inside water-filled compartments of the submarine.
   On Saturday, rescuers used a diving bell to remove 21 sailors
who had been trapped inside the vessel when it sank in about 96
feet of water.
   President Alan Garcia praised the ``heroic valor of the
officers'' aboard the submarine Pacocha, saying the captain and
others perished while attempting to save their fellow crewmen.
   He told reporters that the No. 8 Kyowa-Maru, a 412-ton fishing
boat with a steel hull, struck the stern of the former U.S. Navy
submarine, which flooded with water and quickly sank.
   As the vessel began sinking Friday night, about 24 crewmen were
plucked from the Pacific Ocean after donning life jackets and
jumping from the crippled submarine.
   The Pacocha's commander, Daniel Nieva, died while sealing a
hatch door of the submarine to save the men inside, Garcia said.
   There were no injuries aboard the tuna boat, which reached the
Callao port with cracks in its hull, the Japanese Embassy said. The
boat had a crew of 16 Japanese and five Peruvians.
   Callao officials have banned traffic in the port, Peru's largest
located eight miles west of Lima, until Monday to aid rescue
operations. Officials said an investigation into the cause of the
accident is being conducted.
   The men who were rescued Saturday had sealed themselves off in
dry compartments but their lives became endangered by cholorine gas
emitted when water flooded the vessel's batteries.
   The trapped sailors communicated with rescuers through sensors
attached by divers to the submarine's hull, said a navy spokesman,
Cmdr. Luis Castro.
   He said the accident occurred about three miles west of Callao
as the Pacocha was entering the port and the tuna boat departing.
   The Pacocha, purchased in 1974 from the United States, is one of
12 submarines in Peru's fleet, one of the largest in the Americas.
The 1,870-ton craft, formerly the U.S.S. Atule, was commissioned on
June, 21, 1944, according to Jane's Fighting Ships.
   Navy officials said the recovery equipment brought to Peru by a
U.S. team would be used to refloat the Pacocha.
   They said air is being pumped into the submarine in case the
three missing sailors are still alive. But Garcia and the officials
said it is believed the three are dead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
