<2ND_LINE>AM-KKK-Dream Rallies, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0746,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>KKK Preaches White Power At Rally Near Civil Rights Gathering</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `The atmosphere...', to UPDATE with 14
arrested; SUBS 5th graf, `About 800,' to UPDATE to 900 police
officers; SUBS 7th graf, `Mounted police...', with description of
crowd; INSERTS three grafs after 8th graf, `Three whites...,' to
UPDATE with march to rally and quotes. Picks up 9th graf pvs, `In
1966...;.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROCKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hooded Ku Klux Klansmen preaching white supremacy
staged a rally Sunday near a multiracial gathering commemorating
Martin Luther King Jr., as hundreds of club-carrying police tried
to keep the crowds under control.
   Fourteen people were arrested, most for disorderly conduct, in a
tense afternoon at Marquette Park, where similar rallies sparked
violence and resulted in 17 arrests two years ago.
   ``We had no idea that we'd both be here on the same day, but we
are damn proud to be here for the white race,'' an unidentified
klansman wearing a white hood told an all-white crowd of about 500.
Some members of the crowd held Nazi flags and wore ``White Power''
T-shirts.
   A line of uniformed policemen and wooden barriers kept the crowd
about 40 feet from the stage.
   About 900 police officers, some on horses and other carrying
clubs, filled the park and separated the KKK rally from the
multiracial group that gathered about a half-mile away for a later
rally.
   ``It might be legal to give (the KKK) a permit to spread hatred
and violence, but it's immoral,'' said Dee D. Smith Simmons, an
organizer of the Dream Day Quest, commemorating the 25th
anniversary of King's famous ``I Have A Dream'' speech.
   Mounted police blocked a crowd of several hundred Klan
sympathizers, some shouting ``White Power,'' who tried to break
away from the rally and march to the gathering of about 200 blacks,
whites and Hispanics.
   Three whites, including a woman wearing a T-shirt with the
``White Power'' slogan, were taken away in police wagons, but
officers refused to say why.
   About 150 police officers surrounded a separate multiracial
crowd of about 300 who marched from a nearby church to attend the
King rally, which continued after the Klansmen began dispersing.
Officers fended off several hundred Klan sympathizers who tried to
taunt the marchers.
   ``I'm thankful that the police are here but (the Klan members)
are the ones who are frightened. ... I feel some pity and a lot of
irritation,'' said Rosetta Martin, a white woman from suburban
Hazel Crest.
   ``We organized this to demonstrate to all of Chicago that the
days of racial division are over,'' the Rev. B. Herbert Martin, the
city's commissioner of human relations, said at the King rally.
   In 1966, King led a protest march into Marquette Park, where he
was greeted by a crowd of whites throwing stones.
   Ten years ago, a neo-Nazi group threatened to march through
suburban Skokie, whose 69,000 residents include 23,000 Jews. That
march was called off after lawsuits and community pressure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
