<2ND_LINE>AM-Northern Ireland, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0665,0699</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bombings, Shootings Ripple Across Northern Ireland</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with more violence; picks up
18th pvs: Hundreds of...; Edits throughout to tighten</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gangs of youths threw bombs and
hijacked trucks in west Belfast for a second night Sunday after a
convicted IRA guerrilla was extradited from the Irish Republic.
   At least 16 people were wounded in the rash of shootings,
bombings and other attacks that police blamed on the Irish
Republican Army. Police said there were no serious injuries.
   Violence was reported throughout Northern Ireland after Robert
Russell, a convicted IRA guerrilla, was extradited to Northern
Ireland to complete a prison term for attempted murder and to face
new charges of prison escape.
   In the neighboring Irish Republic, three police officers were
hurt Saturday during a clash as a convoy crossed into Northern
Ireland.
   Since Saturday, there were 193 attacks on police units, 23
shooting incidents, 17 bombings and 56 hijackings of cars, vans and
buses, police said. Some vehicles were set afire, blown up or left
with bombs that were defused by security forces.
   They said 11 police officers, one soldier and four civilians
were wounded in the two days of violence. Bombings were reported in
Belfast, Newry and Londonderry.
   On Sunday, a bomb was thrown at a police station in mainly
Catholic west Belfast, several vehicles were hijacked, and many
gasoline bombs were thrown at police, said a spokesman for the
Royal Ulster Constabulary, the province's police force. However, he
said no injuries were reported in those incidents.
   Earlier Sunday, a calf grazing on a military shooting range was
killed when it set off a bomb apparently meant for locally
recruited soldiers who train there.
   Police said the calf probably triggered the bomb by stepping on
a pressure plate or tripwire on a footpath used by soldiers at the
range at Portballintrae in County Antrim on Northern Ireland's
north coast.
   Chief Inspector Ian Williamson, responsible for policing the
Falls Road area of west Belfast, told the British Broadcasting
Corp. that the violence was planned by the IRA and its legal
political wing, Sinn Fein.
   ``They may claim or give the impression that Russell was the
reason, but it was just the excuse. This day would have come
regardless of whatever reason they dreamed up for it,'' Williamson
said.
   The predominantly Roman Catholic Irish Republican Army is
fighting to unite Northern Ireland with the overwhelmingly Catholic
Irish Republic.
   Bombs began exploding hours after Russell was extradited to
Northern Ireland.
   Hundreds of IRA supporters clashed with police in Dublin and the
border village of Carrickarnon early Saturday to protest Russell's
extradition, police and witnesses said.
   In Dublin, about 80 supporters who had staged an all-night vigil
in front of Mountjoy prison attacked police with bottles and tried
to knock them off motorcycles as they prepared to transport Russell
50 miles to the border.
   Other demonstrators lay in the road to try to block the convoy
and more violence flared when police began dragging them away.
   Russell, 30, escaped from Northern Ireland's Maze Prison in a
mass breakout by IRA inmates in September 1983. He fled to Ireland
and was arrested in Dublin in 1984. The last legal bid to stop his
extradition failed in the High Court in Dublin on Friday.
   Several hundred demonstrators waited in heavy rain for Russell's
convoy at Carrickarnon inside the Irish Republic on the road
between Dublin and Belfast, Irish police said.
   Before the convoy arrived, they attacked police with stones,
bottles and fists. Chief Superintendent John Nolan of the Garda
Siochana, Ireland's police force, said three officers were hurt in
the fighting.
   Some protesters sat in the road to form a human barricade
against the police van carrying Russell, but the van avoided them
by veering off the road and speeding across a field.
   Police said Russell was handed over to Northern Ireland police,
put in a helicopter and flown 30 miles to Lisburn near Belfast.
After a brief court appearance he was returned to the top-security
Maze Prison.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
