<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Wildfires-MakingAStand     08-28 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wildfires-Making A Stand,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Giant Effort Mounted To Choke Blaze Threatening Towns</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XYS1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHOSHONE NATIONAL FOREST, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters torched more
than 500 acres of timber Sunday to make a dramatic goal-line stand
against the leading edge of the largest and perhaps most stubborn
of the blazes in and around Yellowstone National Park.
   ``This fire has kicked us for months. Now we're going to kick it
back,'' Forest Service fire information office Pat Kaunert said.
``We've got to sacrifice this in order to save the timber base and
these towns. This is where we make a stand.''
   Seven bulldozers cleared a six-mile, 70-foot-wide ``freeway''
through the pines Saturday and Sunday before the huge ``backfire''
was set. A ``hot shot'' crew of 19 used drip torches loaded with
diesel fuel and gasoline to torch the acreage between the safety
swath and the 182,000-acre Clover Mist blaze, which has moved to
within a few miles of U.S. Highway 212 which skirts the
Wyoming-Montano border and the communities of Crandall, Wyo., and
Cooke City, Mont.
   Flames rose 100 feet into the air and dense smoke billowed over
the valley as the new fire burned back toward the most aggressive
edge of Clover Mist. About 200 firefighters stood guard at the edge
of the blaze, armed with shovels and fire hoses.
   The Forest Service, eager for its first victory against the
fire, had to wait until late afternoon for proper conditions.
Helicopters and airplanes loaded with water and fire retardant
stood by in case the wind shifted and blew flames back at the
firefighters.
   ``This is the moment we've been waiting for,'' Kaunert said.
``If the fire gets over (Highway) 212, we'd be in a very bad
position to defend the towns.''
   The backfire was indicative of the progress frustrated
firefighters have made against blazes in the last two days. Calm,
favorable winds and cool temperatures at night have slowed the
ravaging flames.
   Earlier, erratic winds kept forcing firefighters to retreat as
Clover Mist moved out of Yellowstone and closer to towns along the
Wyoming-Montana border. And the forecast included more potential
trouble in the form of a new weather system approaching, perhaps as
early as Tuesday, that could bring a change in wind direction and
strong gusts.
   Clover Mist is one of five forest fires burning in Yellowstone
and surrounding forests. Shonsone National Forest borders
Yellowstone's eastern edge.
   Until Sunday, mountainous terrain had kept forest service crews
from mounting a massive assault against Clover Mist.
   ``We had to wait until it got to where we could get at it,''
Kaunert said.
   For more than a week smoke and occasional flames climbing over
the mountains protecting Cooke City had troubled townspeople, who
were told Friday to prepare for an evacuation that was never
necessary. Three Crandall-area ranches were evacuated Saturday.
   In addition to the towns, the fire also threatened some of the
most productive timber land in the Clarks Fork Ranger District.
   ``It's very valuable timber as far as the local economy goes,''
said Forest Service District Ranger Randy Herzberg.
   Enough timber is harvested annually out of the threatened area
to build 100 homes, Herzberg said
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Scott McCartney is the AP Southwest regional
reporter, based in Dallas.
</TEXT>
