<1ST_LINE>u i AM-PlaneCrash-Scene 2ndLd-Writethru   08-28 0722</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plane Crash-Scene, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0751,0746</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witnesses Recall Horror: ``Too Many Dead.''
^Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE death toll; picks up 5th graf
pvs: Miss Kumpf...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Germany-Plane Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMSTEIN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A young medical assistant trembled
and sobbed as she thought of the festive air show that turned into
a fiery tragedy.
   ``There are many children among the dead and injured,'' said
Kris Kumpf, who treated some of the victims.
   ``And the worst part of it is, we're still trying to find some
of the parents.''
   The accident occurred at the U.S. Air Base in Ramstein when a
maneuver by an Italian acrobatic jet team went wrong and sent one
of the aircraft into a crowd of screaming spectators. Two others
crashed, and authorities put the death toll at 46.
   Miss Kumpf said most of the injured had badly burned backs from
when tey turned and tried to run away from the flaming jet.
   After speaking to reporters, Miss Kumpf called her mother to
tell her not to worry.
   ``I'm okay, mama. But there are too many dead,'' she tearfully
said over the telephone.
   Krista Banks, a middle-age West German who works as a waitress
at the U.S. Air Force base at Ramstein, saw the disaster from the
base's control tower.
   ``It was horrible, horrible, a huge shock,'' said Mrs. Banks,
who is married to an American who works for the U.S. Army in the
Kaiserslautern area.
   ``It's going to take a long time to forget this.''
   ``There was a big flash of flame and smoke, and people were
running away. Everyone at the tower was in shock,'' said Mrs. Banks.
   Hundreds of people were walking back to their cars parked
outside the base after the accident. Many of them looked stunned.
Few of them were speaking.
   An old woman cried as a younger woman comforted her and led her
toward their car.
   An elderly West German man said that the accident occurred when
two groups of Italian jets were performing a maneuver just above
the airfield.
   ``Five of the planes came from one direction, and four came head
on in another. A single plane came from yet another direction, and
there was a crash.
   ``All I saw was a big ball of fire,'' said the man, who would
not give his name.
   Hours after the crash, the airfield where the accident occurred
was scattered with paper cups, beer cases, and turned-over lawn
chairs left by fleeing spectators.
   A huge block of scorched debris from one of the three airplanes
involved in the crash lay next to a destroyed truck that caught
fire when it was rammed by the aircraft.
   A smoky stench still clotted the air.
   U.S. Air Force guards escorted reporters who visited the scene
of the disaster, but refused to say anything.
   Traffic was backed up outside the base as ambulances rushed
casualties from the scene to hospitals in the area.
   Mrs. Banks praised emergency rescue efforts during the initial
moments of the tragedy.
   ``Rescue ambulances were very quickly on the way to the scene,''
she said.
   West Germany's ARD television network showed horrifying footage
of Sunday's crash at the Ramstein U.S. Air Base, including the
plane veering out of control already in flames and the spectators'
area looking like a battlefield afterwards.
   The disaster began as the Italian Air Force ``air acrobatic
team'' flew at about 60 meters off the ground in front of a crowd
estimated by Germans to be more than 200,000. Most are Germans and
Americans.
   Suddenly, planes collided in formation, small pieces were seen
flying from the aircraft. A crippled plane veered uncontrollably
out of formation, with flames already coming from the fuselage.
   Spectators looked up to see the plane heading straight toward
them, with many starting to run in panic.
   The Italian Aermacchi MB 339A plowed into a row of cars and
buses, bursting into a ball of flames at least 100 feet high and
wide.
   ``We saw the fireball racing toward us, so we first threw
ourselves down on the ground,'' said Detlef Hosser, an ARD
cameraman.
   Both West German and American rescue squads arrived on the
scene. Helicopters hovered overhead. Rescue workers carried off
some of the dead on stretchers.
   Desperate parents, meanwhile, cried out for missing children.
</TEXT>
