<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Crash-FlyingTeam 1stLd-Writethru   08-28 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Flying Team, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0747,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Famed Aerial Squad Pilots No Stranger To Tragedy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE death toll; picks up 4th
pvs: The three...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Germany-Plane Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Italian air force stunt team whose performance
went tragically awry in West Germany on Sunday has had other
encounters with disaster.
   The latest tragedy was the worst, however. Three pilots of the
famed troupe died Sunday when their sleek fighter jets collided
during a huge air show at the Ramstein U.S. Air Base.
   One of the aircraft plunged into the crowd, and authorities said
at least 46 people overall were killed.
   The three jets were part of a 10-plane Italian Air Force
demonstration team, ``Frecce Tricolori,'' that was flying 65 yards
above the ground.
   The Frecce Tricolori, which means Tri-Color Arrows and refers to
the three-colored Italian flag, was founded in 1930 as a school of
aerobatics. Since 1956, it has been a separate unit of the Italian
air force based at Rivolto.
   Three times before in the last 10 years have members of the
precision team been killed in air crashes. One, Capt. Pier Gianni
Petri, was credited with saving the lives of spectators at a May
29, 1979, air show at Mildehall in Britain by directing his G91 jet
away from the crowd when it crashed.
   Two of the unit's G91 jets collided over the airport at Rivolto
on July 12, 1978, killing one of the two pilots, Capt. Graziano
Carrer. On Sept. 2, 1981, another G91 crashed at Rivolto, killing
Capt. Antonio Gallus.
   The three pilots killed in the collision Sunday at Ramstein were
Lt. Col. Mario Naldini, 41, Lt. Col. Ivo Nutarelli, 38, and Capt.
Giorgio Alessio, 31. Italian Air Force officials said Naldini had
3,900 flight hours, Nutarelli had 3,800 and Alessio had 1,600.
   The men were flying Aermacchi MB 339As, a two-seat attack
aircraft that the Italian air force also uses for pilot training.
   The Frecce Tricolori includes 14 pilots, three technical
officers and 55 specialists.
   Aircraft used by Frecce Tricolori are painted blue with
longitudinal stripes of red, white and green, the colors of the
Italian flag which is known in Italy as the tricolori.
   To be a member of the team, a pilot must have at least six years
of experience and a minimum of 1,000 hours of flight time. Military
officials say that the team members actually have an average of
3,000 flight hours and an average age of 32.
   The team appears at numerous shows in Italy and abroad between
April and October each year and spends the intervening months
practicing its aerobatic routines.
   During a show there are normally nine planes in formation, one
soloist and the commander remains on the field coordinating the
action by radio.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
