<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0711-a0744 08-28 1025</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0711-a0744,980</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Damns Quayle With Faint Praise</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with Quayle, Bush comments, gives new LEDE, edits
2nd graf for transition, INSERTS four grafs after 5th pvs, ``Now
I...that time,'' DELETES 6th graf and picks up 7th pvs, Quayle
attended...South Carolina, SUBS 9th graf, Bush attended...Price
Daniel,'' INSERTING new 10th graf and picking up 10th pvs, Dukakis
went...gubernatorial duties.
   ^By JERRY ESTILL</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen said Sunday that Sen. Dan Quayle probably
could grow into the job of being president if it became necessary,
while Quayle said he's ready for a debate with Bentsen to show
voters who's qualified.
   Bentsen's remarks were the faintest of praise from a 67-year-old
Texas Democrat seeking to contrast his experience with that of a
41-year-old Indiana Republican _ and to make the difference a major
issue in their campaign for vice president.
   Appearing on NBC's ``Meet The Press,'' Bentsen was asked whether
Quayle was qualified to be president.
   ``Frankly, he would not have been on my short list as I look
over my Senate colleagues,'' said Bentsen. ``He obviously was on
the short list of the hard right. ...
   ``Now, I wouldn't say that he couldn't grow into the job; he
probably could. But if a tragedy befell a president, you'd have to
be able to move in immediately and take over and do what has to be
done in facing whatever issues that confront you at that time.''
   Quayle, in an in-flight interview Sunday with The Associated
Press, said he has no quarrel with his Senate colleague Bentsen. In
fact, Quayle focused during his seven-state campaign swing on
Dukakis, saying a victory by the Massachusetts governor would be a
disaster for the country.
   ``I've served with Sen. Bentsen for almost eight years. He is
not the issue,'' Quayle said. ``The issue is Michael Dukakis.
Michael Dukakis' view of America is a much different view than
George Bush's. Michael Dukakis' approach to national defense, his
approach to the economy, his approach to child care _ all of those
approaches are much different than George Bush's.''
   Quayle also said he is not disturbed by polls that show a
majority of the public views Bentsen as more qualified for the vice
presidential spot, and to be president if it comes to that.
   ``The American people are just beginning to see Dan Quayle,'' he
said. ``I'm going to continue to talk about the issues. When we
have the debate between Lloyd Bentsen and Dan Quayle, the American
people will have a lot better picture of who will be the best
qualified vice presidential candidate.''
   Quayle attended church in Sacramento, Calif., and then made the
cross-country flight home to Washington for a couple of days of
rest and planning for this week's swing through Louisiana,
Arkansas, Mississippi, Alabama, Florida, Georgia and South Carolina.
   The contenders for the No. 1 chair in the Oval Office _
Republican George Bush and Democrat Michael Dukakis _ were out and
about, but keeping things low-key.
   Bush attended services at the Episcopal church near the Houston
hotel where he maintains an official address, then took in an
Astros baseball game. Later he attended a memorial service in
Austin for former Texas Gov. Price Daniel.
   During an in-flight interview, Bush commented on his recent
boost in the polls, saying: ``I think it's very encouraging
movement in the polls, but these things change so dramatically. ...
I can't deny it's encouraging, but there's certainly nothing there
that makes me relax.''
   Dukakis went to church and then attended a Sunday afternoon
concert. He planned to spend the next two days in Massachusetts
attending to gubernatorial duties.
   But if Bentsen was the only candidate taking a highly visible
stance Sunday, he was not the only political figure doing do.
   Jesse Jackson assured another group of television interviewers _
on ABC's ``This Week With David Brinkley'' _ that he was behind the
Dukakis-Bentsen ticket, but left it a little fuzzy to what extent.
   To a questioner's suggestion that he had not quite made up his
mind on how hard to play the game, Jackson said:
   ``Well, I've made up my mind, but of course, I need signals of
sensitivity that reflect the urgency of now. We must keep expanding
beyond the present Democratic base with an intense voter
registration campaign that has not yet been agreed upon and
planned. There must be more inclusion at the senior policy
positions in order that there might be more sensitivity around
Governor Dukakis.''
   Jackson said it was fine for the Democratic ticket to reach out
to middle-of-the road Democrats who have been voting for Ronald
Reagan.
   At the same time, he said, ``I would think the Democrats'
strength is not between the 45-yard lines ... this obsession to
recall Reagan Democrats who are with Quayle under the Bush.''
   Later, Jackson said, ``My concern is that if we're going to win,
it will be by the margin of our enthusiasm of our expanded
participation. Therefore my emphasis, the way I'm helping the
ticket at this point, is engaging in massive registration.''
   Bentsen's remarks about Quayle's experience were a continuation
of the Democratic strategy of calling attention to the better-known
Texas senator's 17{ years in the Senate compared to Quayle's
7{-year tenure.
   Asked about the flap over Quayle's membership in the Indiana
National Guard during the Vietnam War, Bentsen noted that all
candidates for national office are subject to intense media
scrutiny.
   ``I think that has now been done insofar as Senator Quayle and
his decision to go into the Guard and what motivated him and how he
was able to enter that Guard,'' he said. ``And now I think we
should move on to other issues.''
   Bentsen acknowledged that he has differences with Dukakis on a
variety of issues, but insisted that was a plus for the Democratic
ticket.
   ``I think what you're seeing is a situation where Michael
Dukakis was not looking for a clone of himself,'' he said. ``He was
reaching out to the center. It shows something of the integrity of
this man, that he is not afraid to listen to a different
viewpoint.''
</TEXT>
