<1ST_LINE>d i AM-Earthquake     08-28 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earthquake,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll Climbs To Nearly 1,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Search teams recovered the bodies of 35
more victims of the Aug. 21 earthquake in the mountainous region
between Nepal and India, raising the disaster's death toll to
nearly 1,000, officials said Sunday.
   Nepal's Home Ministry said officials have confirmed the deaths
of 708 people in Nepal from the Aug. 21 quake, 35 above its
previous count. India has reported 277 Indians perished, making the
death toll 985 for both countries.
   The Home Ministry also said 1,551 Nepalese were injured and 171
people in serious condition were flown by helicopters from the
remote region to hospitals in Biratnagar, 140 miles southeast of
Katmandu.
   Heavy weekend rains blocked the medical evacuation Sunday and
also caused landslides and flooding that claimed at least 12 more
lives, according to the Nepalese news agency RSS. It said five
people were missing.
   RSS said 12 people were killed by landslides in villages some
200 miles west of Katmandu.
   Five people were carried away by surging waters of the flooding
Narayani River 75 miles southwest of the capital, according to the
agency.
   The quake, which measured 6.5 on the Richter scale, destroyed or
damaged 17,875 houses in 24 districts in Nepal.
   More than 10,000 Nepalese were killed in a major quake in 1934.
   The Richter scale measures energy released by an earthquake as
recorded on seismographs, and each increase by one number means the
ground motion is 10 times greater. A quake measuring 6 can cause
severe damage and one registering 7 is considered a major quake.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880828-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-88 2224EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     08-28 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Aquino Visits Brunei, Troops on Alert</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino left Monday
for a three-day visit to Brunei and troops in Manila were ordered
on full alert to guard against any attempted coup during her
absence.
   At least 16 people were killed in scattered actions Sunday. A
police captain was shot Sunday in a Manila suburb and 15 people
were killed in fighting between guerrillas of the communists' New
People's Army and anti-communist vigilantes on the central island
of Negros.
   ``We have assured the president that she can make her trip to
Brunei .... and she can come back here and find the country safe
and secure,'' Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos told reporters Sunday.
   Troops have been placed on alert during Mrs. Aquino's previous
foreign trips but there have been no coup attempts while she was
abroad.
   She has visited Singapore, Indonesia, the United States, Japan,
China, Hong Kong, Switzerland and Italy since becoming president in
February 1986 after the civilian-military uprising that toppled
President Ferdinand Marcos. He is now living in exile in Hawaii.
   Mrs. Aquino, leader of one of Southeast Asia's poorest nations,
is to hold talks with Brunei's ruler, Sultan Hassanal Bokiah, one
of the world's richest men.
   She said in a brief departure statement her visit is to improve
relations with a fellow member of the seven-country Association of
Southeast Asian Nations. She also will meet with Brunei businessmen
to encourage investments in the Philippines.
   Officials gave these accounts of the killings Sunday;
   Four gunmen killed Capt. Roberto Basco, the anti-narcotics
commander in Lucena City, as he and his family left a Roman
Catholic church in Pasig. Basco's wife and 18-year-old daughter
were wounded in the attack.
   Communist rebels have killed scores of policemen and soldiers
this year but police said Basco may have been slain by common
criminals.
   On Negros island, anti-communist vigilantes killed a suspected
guerrilla and in a reprisal raid about 100 communist rebels killed
nine of the vigilantes. Luisito Pedro, a vigilantes leader, said
his men killed five guerrillas in the fighting.
   On Sunday, Mrs. Aquino praised soldiers killed defending her
government during a coup attempt last year.
   Speaking at the military cemetery at Fort Bonifacio on the
anniversay of the attempted Coup on Aug. 28, 1987, she said:
   ``They fell on this day last year in the greatest battle waged
to defend our newly restored democracy.''
   At least 53 people were killed and more than 300 wounded when
mutinous soldiers led by former Lt. Col. Gregorio Honasan tried to
storm the presidential palace.
   Honasan was captured last December but escaped in April and
remains at large.
   Mrs. Aquino made no mention Sunday of opposition moves to forge
a new alliance.
   Vice President Salvador Laurel announced on Saturday the
formation of the Union for National Action alliance.
   Laurel said Mrs. Aquino's ``blundering and immoral
administration'' would lead the country to disaster.
   Last September Laurel resigned as foreign secretary.
</TEXT>
