<HEAD>Oil Pipeline Explosion Kills 11</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An oil pipeline exploded in eastern Veracruz
state, killing at least 11 people and injuring several others, the
government oil monopoly Pemex said Sunday.
   The explosion occurred at 5:00 a.m. Sunday (7:00 a.m. EDT),
roughly five hours after a leak from the 30-inch pipeline was
discovered, Pemex said in a statement.
   Workers had succeeded in shutting off the flow of oil when the
leak caught fire and the pipeline exploded, Pemex said. The blaze
was brought under control at 6:40 a.m. (8:40 a.m. EDT).
   Company officials were investigating the cause of the explosion,
Pemex said. Pemex did not release the victims' identities and did
not say how many were injured in the explosion.
   The incident occurred between the towns of Juan Diaz Covarrubias
and Juan R. Cabada on the Poza Rica-Nuevo Teapa pipeline, about 270
miles km) east of Mexico City.
   Pemex director Francisco Rojas ordered an investigation into the
incident, the statement said.
