<FILEID>AP-NR-08-28-88 2008EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-DeKalbBreak-Up     08-28 0892</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-DeKalb Break-Up,0918</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DeKalb Breaking Up To Make Up With Analysts, Drive Up Stock Price</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: This is for Monday PMs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Breaking up may be hard to do, but it's a great
way to get the attention of the people who matter most, Bruce
Bickner might say.
   Bickner is neither a lonely hearts columnist nor a pop
psychologist offering advice to the lovelorn. He is president of
DeKalb Corp., an Illinois conglomerate that is about to break up
into three, possibly four, publicly traded companies.
   The scheduled Aug. 31 split will allow each of DeKalb's lines of
business _ oil and gas exploration, agricultural genetics, oil-well
servicing and irrigation-equipment manufacturing _ to stand alone.
   Investors have been gobbling up DeKalb's stock in anticipation
of the restructuring. In the 10 months since the company announced
the plan, its stock price has soared from about $20 to near $32.
   But behind the rising value of DeKalb's stock are the ``buy''
recommendations of research analysts who largely had ignored the
company until its break-up plans became apparent.
   DeKalb had net income of $42.9 million on revenues of $367
million last year, compared with a 1986 loss of $50.7 million on
revenues of $406.7 million. But despite the company's greatly
improved performance since 1986, DeKalb found few analysts willing
to follow a firm with such disparate interests.
   ``The large (investment) houses just don't seem to cooperate
across industry lines,'' Bickner said in a recent interview in
Chicago. DeKalb is based in the northern Illinois city of DeKalb.
   ``Somebody who covers the food industry and would, by nature,
understand DeKalb's agricultural business would be reluctant to
cover DeKalb because they don't know what to do with the oil
business,'' he said. ``If they're writing a report on DeKalb and
most of DeKalb's assets are in oil and gas reserves, what are they
going to say about the stock?''
   Several analysts now following the company agreed that DeKalb's
diversification, regarded as a plus in the 1960s and 1970s, worked
against its stock value in the past two years even though the
50-year-old firm clearly was recovering from its weak period of the
early 1980s.
   ``I'm an oil analyst,'' said Charles M. Strain of Houston-based
Lovett Mitchell Webb & Garrison, ``and it's hard enough for me to
follow 20 or 30 oil companies without following one that's at least
as subject to the vagaries of the hybrid corn seed business as it
is to the vagaries of the oil business.
   ``I get very uncomfortable with my knowledge of the seed
business,'' he added.
   Research analysts prefer simplicity, said Michael J. Harris, an
energy analyst with Morgan Keegan & Co. of Memphis who began
recommending DeKalb's stock last year.
   ``Logical diversification makes some kind of sense,'' he said.
``But when you're in the agriculture business and you also own gas
and oil _ the ag analysts don't understand oil and gas, and the oil
analysts don't understand agriculture.''
   DeKalb's restructuring plan calls for distributing a half share
of stock in the agricultural company, to be called DeKalb Genetics
Corp., and one share of stock in Pride Petroleum Services Inc., the
oil-well servicing company, for each share of DeKalb Corp. stock.
   DeKalb Corp. then will be renamed DeKalb Energy Co. and will
concentrate on oil and gas exploration.
   Finally, the company plans an initial public offering of the
Lindsay Manufacturing Co., its wholly owned irrigation
manufacturing and marketing division. John Stafford, DeKalb's chief
financial officer, said the Lindsay offering is tentatively planned
for September, but the date will depend on market conditions and
the timing of regulatory approval.
   DeKalb currently has two types of stock: class A voting stock,
which is not publicly traded, and class B non-voting stock, which
is publicly traded. The Roberts family, which founded DeKalb in the
1930s, controls 60 percent of the class A stock and thus controls
the company.
   After the split, the Roberts family will retain control of
DeKalb Energy and DeKalb Genetics. But Pride Petroleum will have
only one class of stock, all voting. Only 20 percent of that stock
will be owned by the Roberts family.
   ``The family is retaining its absolute control of the genetics
and energy business but giving up absolute control of Pride,''
Bickner said.
   Analysts have estimated the aggregate value of the companies
after the spinoff at $34 to $40 a share. DeKalb Energy is expected
to trade around $20 a share, DeKalb Genetics at about $10 and
DeKalb Corp. at around $7.
   In addition to demonstrating the importance of analyst coverage
to a stock's value, DeKalb's break-up illustrates the declining
popularity among investors of conglomerates in favor of so-called
``pure plays'' _ companies with only one line of business.
   ``I think the last time it was an advantage to be a conglomerate
was in the late '60s. In the late '60s they were magic,'' said
Strain.
   Analyst Harris agreed.
   ``Twenty years ago there was a mindset among corporate
executives that they were going to be portfolio managers; they
would buy and sell companies and get big and diversify and that was
good,'' he said.
   ``But in the last few years it's finally dawned on people that
managers should not be portfolio managers,'' Harris added. ``They
should run businesses and let the investors arrange their own
portfolios.''
</TEXT>
