<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Westinghouse-Labor     08-28 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Westinghouse-Labor,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Westinghouse Reaches Tentative Agreement With Four Unions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Westinghouse Electric Corp. reached tentative
national labor agreements Sunday with four unions representing
14,000 workers.
   Details of the three-year agreement were not announced, pending
notification of the union membership. Ratification votes are
expected to take place over the next two weeks.
   ``We have arrived at an innovative pay and benefits package that
is uniquely tailored to the needs of Westinghouse and its
employees,'' said George Dorman, Westinghouse vice president of
human resources.
   Dorman said he was optimistic the rank-and-file membership would
ratify the pact. The current pact expired at midnight Sunday.
   The four unions are: the International Union of Electronic,
Electrical, Salaried, Machine and Furniture Workers, or the IUE,
representing 3,000 workers; the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers, or the IBEW, representing 5,600 employees; the
Federation of Westinghouse Independent Salaried Unions,
representing 5,400 workers; and the United Electrical, Radio and
Machine Workers of America, or the UE, representing 130 workers.
   The unions represent about 5,075 employees in western
Pennsylvania and 9,000 workers throughout the country.
   About 31 other unions representing Westinghouse's remaining
11,000 employees negotiate independent agreements plant-by-plant,
said Westinghouse spokesman Jim Schmitt.
   General Electric Co., a Westinghouse competitor whose labor
contracts influence the industry, agreed in July with the IUE, the
IBEW and the UE on a three-year contract that raises the average
hourly GE wage from $12.02 to $13.40.
   The average hourly wage at Westinghouse was about $12.50,
Schmitt said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
